<TITLE>Big Dummy's Guide to the Internet - Smiley Dictionary</TITLE>
<P>Go to the <A HREF="bdg_289.html">previous</A>, <A HREF="bdg_291.html">next</A> section.<P>
<H1><A NAME="SEC293" HREF="bdg_toc.html#SEC293">The Unofficial Smiley Dictionary</A></H1>
<iMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC=logos/bdgtti.gif>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_291.html#SEC294">Basic Smileys</A>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_292.html#SEC295">Widely used Smileys</A>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_293.html#SEC296">Midget Smileys</A>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_294.html#SEC297">Mega Smileys</A>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_295.html#SEC298">Usenet Smileys</A>
<LI><A HREF="bdg_296.html#SEC299">Emotional Smileys</A>
</UL>
<P>
This <i>Unofficial Smiley Dictionary</I> is only one of many different
collections by various "editors" you'll come across at many places on
the Net, e.g. you can get "The-Smiley-File" from <B>gopher.world.std.com</B>;
<A NAME="IDX587"></A>
and even a complete booklet has been written on smileys and is available as:
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>David W. Sanderson</B> (ed.), <i>Smileys</I>, O'Reilly &#38; Associates,
Sebastopol, CA. 93 pages. ISBN 1-56592-041-4. Price $5.95 (US).
</BLOCKQUOTE>
