<TITLE>Overview of ONR 4331-001-srp-01  (Research Proposal and Quarterly
Report)
</TITLE>
<H1>Computing with Relations </H1>
<H2>Combinatory Constraint Logic Programming, Types and Allegories</H2>


<iMG SRC="/~lipton/texfiles/onr94/MTT.ps">

<H2>ONR Contract Number 4331-001-srp-01 </H2>

<ADDRESS>
PI:
Peter Freyd, 
Department of Mathematics, 
University of Pennsylvania, 
Philadelphia, PA 19104,
pjf@saul.cis.upenn.edu<p>

and<p>
co-PI:
   Jim Lipton, 
   Dept. of Mathematics,            
   Wesleyan University,             
   Middletown CT  06459-0128,     
  lipton@allegory.cs.wesleyan.edu
</ADDRESS>                        


<hr>
<H3>Objectives</H3>

 To develop mathematical foundations and techniques for exploiting the calculus
of relations as a programming discipline, and as a framework for
<OL>

<L1> - extending and providing categorical semantics for declarative
programming with constraints.<p>    

<L1> - extracting  relational algorithms from specifications and
proving them correct.<p>  

<L1> - combining declarative and functional programming.

</OL>

To explore applications to non-determinism and computing with partial
information.  


<hr>
<H2> Other key objectives of the research program</H2>



<UL>
   
<LI> To develop a theory of relational computation: determine the
computational strength and semantics of different relational calculi for
computation.  Explore  denotational, operational and
realizability semantics for such disciplines. Address such 
questions as: which classes of functions are computable in the different
calculi, how does one capture just total, feasible or typable
computations through restrictions of the relational calculi, etc.  

<LI> To develop Category-theoretic foundations of logic programming.

<LI> To develop relational programming with partial information in the
form of <em> constraints</em>, i.e.,  with
relational inputs and outputs. To develop a systematic
approach to high-level program optimization via transformations of relational
programs by rewriting at the relational level, and studying  the
relevant confluence and Church Rosser properties.
 
To study equational and Horn presentations of relational theories with
transitive closure and other recursive operators. Also:

<LI> To bring out the combinatory nature of
database and logic programming (Prolog and generalizations), and especially
constraint logic programming as relational programming languages.

Systematically analyze and extend Tarski's variable-elimination
algorithm in the context of non-Boolean and higher order frameworks of
Division and Power Allegories.
        
<LI> To provide a natural declarative extension of typed,
polymorphic functional programming, that integrates the semantics of both
declarative and functional paradigms.
To explore further the use of denotational, PERs and other categorical
models developed by the first author and
other researchers for type theories and polymorphism 
to include declarative and relational languages.
</UL>

<H3>Proposal and Reports</H3>
<!--<a HREF="/~lipton/ONR/onr9.ps">
<!--Annual Report: 1993.</a><p>

<!--<a HREF="/~lipton/ONR/onrProp91.ps">
