<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT18-B35-46</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA097-001045-B023-137</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://allegory.cs.wesleyan.edu:80/Math/courses/math228.F95/html/mathproj.html 129.133.30.49 19970215101453 text/html 13091
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 10:14:00 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.1
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 19:52:40 GMT
</DOCHDR>
Integers and Natural Numbers

Natural Numbers:
     When one remembers back to first grade and the first steps of one's mathematical
training, the first mathematical concept learned was how to count.  0, 1, 2, 3, 4, etc. are the
building blocks of our current mathematical knowledge.  In first grade a child does not know
this, but those numbers being counted actually comprise the natural number set which is the
oldest and most basic number set.
     Natural numbers could be defined as whole integers without negative numbers.  0, 1,
2, and so forth are all natural numbers; however, -1, -2, -3, and the kind are not natural
numbers.  The set of natural number does not include fractions, thus 1/4 is not a natural
number.  Thus the formal definition of the natural number set could be stated as:
          N = {0, 1, 2, 3, . . ., 1000, 1001, . . .} - the collection of all
          such whole, positive, "natural" numbers.
          The natural number set has certain physical features to which it adheres.  The first is
that one
number in the set is always greater than or equal to another number in the set.  The natural
number set also fulfills some mathematical functions.  The sum of any two numbers within
the set will always be another number within the set.  The product of any two numbers within
the set will always be another number within the set.  Finally, one natural number raised to
the power of another natural number will always be a natural number.  However, the natural
number set does not always fulfill the subtraction and division functions, for 3-5 does not
have an answer from within the set, as well 3/5 does not have an answer from within the set.
     The question now becomes, Is the natural number set an integral domain?  The set
will only be an integral domain if multiplication and addition hold for the set (which they do)
and each of nine mathematical postulates hold for the set (which will be examined now).
     I. Closure: This has already been examined, and the set does have closure.
     II. Uniqueness: If a=a' and b=b' the a+b=a'+b' and ab=a'b'.  This should be fairly
obvious for the set since there is only one of each number in the set then if a=a' and b=b'
then clearly a+b=x and a'+b'=x and since x=x then a+b=a'+b'.  The same method holds for
multiplication.  
     III. Commutative Laws: a+b=b+a and ab=ba.  Order simply does not matter in the +
and x of the natural number set.  Common sense dictates that 2+3=3+2 since they both equal
5.  The same is true of multiplication.  (Or I could use this algebraic which works equally
well for + and x)
          a+b=b+a        Given
          x=b+a               Let a+b=x
          x-a=b               Subtracting a from both sides
          a+b-a=b        Substituting back in for x
          b=b            Simple algebra      
                         Q.E.D.
               IV. Associative Laws: a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c and a(bc)=(ab)c.  Much like the
reasoning
behind the commutative law, the associative law works under the same assumption that the
order of + or x does not really matter.  If one has three elements a, b, and c, within the sum
of the three will be the same regardless of the order of +.  (Or I could use this algebraic
argument which works equally well for both + and x)
          a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c     Given
          a+x=y+c        Let b+c=x and a+b=y
          a-c=y-x        Subtracting c and x from both sides
          a-c=(a+b)-(b+c)     Substituting back for x and y
          a-c=a-c        Distributive Law
                         Q.E.D.
               V. Distributive law: a(b+c)=ab+ac.  One could look at the distributive law from
one of
two angles.  Either it could be seen from the logical standpoint that since order of operation
in the set does not matter, then the distributive law clearly holds.  Or one can look at the
proof of the distributive law from an algebraic point of view:
          a(b+c)=ab+ac   Given 
          ax=ab+ac if         Let b+c=x
          0=ab+ac-ax          You subtract ax from both sides you get
          0=a(b+c-x)          Since a is a common factor of all three
          0=a[b+c-(b+c)] Substituting b+c back in for x
          0=a(0)         From uniqueness b+c=b+c
          0=0            Since 0 time anything equals 0
                         Q.E.D.
               VI. Zero: a+0=a.  The reason why this rule holds for the set is inherent within the
number 0.  0 is a neutral element, thus it does not alter the number to which it is added, thus
any number a when added to zero would simply be the number a.
     VII. Unity: (a)(1)=a.  Once again this holds simply because of the fact that 1 is, by its
nature, a neutral element for multiplication.  Thus whenever 1 in multiplied by any other
number from the set, the answer will simply be the number.
          Note: Because of the simplicity of postulates VI and VII and
          also the fact that the postulates are analogous, 0 and 1 are
          referred to as "identity elements" for addition and multiplication
          respectively. (B &McL)?
               VIII. Additive Inverse: For each a in set D, a+x=0 has a solution x in D.  This is
where the natural number set breaks down, for it fails to fulfill this postulate.  This is fairly
obvious, since there are no negative numbers within the natural number set, then 1+x=0 does
not have a solution.
     IX. Cancellation Law: If c does not =0 and ca=cb, then a=b. This can be quite easily
proven algebraically:
          ca=cb               Given
          0=cb-ca        Subtracting ca from both sides
          0=c(b-a)       Using distributive law
          0=b-a               Since c does not =0 and / both sides by c
          a=b            Adding a to both side
                         Q.E.D.
          After testing the natural number set with each of the nine postulates, it is clear that
the natural number set is not an integral domain.  This is because of the fact that the set fails
the additive inverse postulate.  However, there is another set of numbers which corrects this
problem: the integers.

Integers:
     The set of numbers known as integers could be seen as a solution to the problems
which arise in the natural number set.  It is about second grade when the concept of integers
is generally introduced.  One could look at it from the perspective of a child who, at lunch,
borrows a sandwich from another second grader.  The next week the child is asked to repay
his debt, and although both children have an intuitive sense of what this means, neither can
express the debt on paper.  This is where the integers are introduced.  
     Integers encompass all numbers which are included in the natural number set, but also
encompass all of the negative whole numbers as well.  Thus numbers such as 0, 1, 2, 3 are in
the set of integers, but now -1, -2, -3 are also included in the set.  In fact, for every positive
number in the set of integers there is also a number equal in value, but opposite in sign. 
Integers, like natural numbers, do not include fraction such as 1/4.  The formal definition of
integers could be stated as:
          Z= {. . .-1001, -1000, . . .-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, . . . 1000, 1001, . . .}-
          The collection of all such whole numbers, positive, negative or
          zero.
          Much like the natural numbers, the integers have certain physical features to which it
adheres. 
In fact, many of its features are the same as the natural numbers.  Like the natural numbers,
one number from the set is always greater than or equal to another number from the set.  The
integers also fulfill some mathematical operations.  The sum of any two integers will always
be another integer, also the product of any two integers will be another integer.  However,
unlike the natural numbers, subtraction does hold for the integers, such that any integer
subtracted from another integer will yield another integer.   Also unlike the natural numbers,
for the integers, an integer cannot always be raised to the power of another integer, e.g.    
2^-2=1/4, which is quite obviously not an integer.  Division does not hold for the integers for
the same reason that a fractional answer, i.e. 2/5, is possible.
     The question now becomes, Is the integer set an integral domain?  One would guess
so, due to both the likeness in names as well as the fact that integers were invented to solve
the problem of the natural numbers.  However we still must prove it, and the set will only be
an integral domain if multiplication and addition hold for the set (which they do) and each of
nine mathematical postulates hold for the set (which will be examined now).
     I. Closure: This has already been examined, and the set does have closure.
     II. Uniqueness: If a=a' and b=b' the a+b=a'+b' and ab=a'b'.  This should be fairly
obvious for the set since there is only one of each number in the set then if a=a' and b=b'
then clearly a+b=x and a'+b'=x and since x=x then a+b=a'+b'.  The same method holds for
multiplication.  
     III. Commutative Laws: a+b=b+a and ab=ba.  Order simply does not matter in the +
and x of the integer set.  Common sense dictates that 2+3=3+2 since they both equal 5.  The
same is true of multiplication.  (Or one could use this algebraic which works equally well for
+ and x)
          a+b=b+a        Given
          x=b+a               Let a+b=x
          x-a=b               Subtracting a from both sides
          a+b-a=b        Substituting back in for x
          b=b            Simple algebra      
                         Q.E.D.
               IV. Associative Laws: a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c and a(bc)=(ab)c.  Much like the
reasoning
behind the commutative law, the associative law works under the same assumption that the
order of + or x does not really matter.  If one has three elements a, b, and c, within the sum
of the three will be the same regardless of the order of +.  (Or I could use this algebraic
argument which works equally well for both + and x)
          a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c     Given
          a+x=y+c        Let b+c=x and a+b=y
          a-c=y-x        Subtracting c and x from both sides
          a-c=(a+b)-(b+c)     Substituting back for x and y
          a-c=a-c        Distributive Law
                         Q.E.D.
               V. Distributive law: a(b+c)=ab+ac.  One could look at the distributive law from
one of
two angles.  Either it could be seen from the logical standpoint that since order of operation
in the set does not matter, then the distributive law clearly holds.  Or one can look at the
proof of the distributive law from an algebraic point of view:
          a(b+c)=ab+ac   Given 
          ax=ab+ac if         Let b+c=x
          0=ab+ac-ax          You subtract ax from both sides you get
          0=a(b+c-x)          Since a is a common factor of all three
          0=a[b+c-(b+c)] Substituting b+c back in for x
          0=a(0)         From uniqueness b+c=b+c
          0=0            Since 0 time anything equals 0
                         Q.E.D.
               VI. Zero: a+0=a.  The reason why this rule holds for the set is inherent within the
number 0.  0 is a neutral element, thus it does not alter the number to which it is added, thus
any number a when added to zero would simply be the number a.
     VII. Unity: (a)(1)=a.  Once again this holds simply because of the fact that 1 is, by its
nature, a neutral element for multiplication.  Thus whenever 1 in multiplied by any other
number from the set, the answer will simply be the number.
          Note: Because of the simplicity of postulates VI and VII and
          also the fact that the postulates are analogous, 0 and 1 are
          referred to as "identity elements" for addition and multiplication
          respectively. (B &McL)
               VIII. Additive Inverse: For each a in set D, a+x=0 has a solution x in D.  This
was
where the natural number set failed.  But here the integers succeed and the reason is simply
due to the construction of the set.  Since the set of integers consist of all whole numbers,
positive or negative, then for every a, there must be -a.  Thus when -a is substituted in for x,
the additive inverse postulate holds, for a+(-a)=0.
     IX. Cancellation Law: If c does not =0 and ca=cb, then a=b. This can be quite easily
proven algebraically:
          ca=cb               Given
          0=cb-ca        Subtracting ca from both sides
          0=c(b-a)       Using distributive law
          0=b-a               Since c does not =0 and / both sides by c
          a=b            Adding a to both side
                         Q.E.D.
     After testing the integers it becomes clear that the set of intergers is actually an
integral domain.
</DOC>
