<BODY>

<H1>1. Rings 'n Things</H1>

<P>
Several &quot;number systems&quot; should be familiar to the reader
from previous experience with &quot;daily mathematics&quot;; these
may include the systems we shall be referring to, in what follows,
as:
<P>
<B>N</B>: the system of &quot;first grade&quot; whole numbers
(integers), zero and greater;
<P>
<B>Z</B>: the system of &quot;second grade&quot; integers, positive,
negative, and zero;
<P>
<B>Q</B>: the system of &quot;third grade&quot; rational numbers
(fractions of integers);
<P>
<B>R</B>: the system of real numbers, as encountered, say, in
Calculus;
<P>
<B>C</B>: the system of complex numbers (&quot;real part plus
imaginary part&quot;), as encountered, say, in using the quadratic
formula for finding the roots of a quadratic polynomial.
<P>
For the first four of these number systems, if perhaps not for
all five, the reader should be familiar both with the conventional
ways of adding -- or multiplying -- two numbers <i>a</I> and <i>b</I>
so as to obtain their sum <i>a </I>+ <i>b</I> -- or their product
<i>a </I>&#183; <i>b --</I> and with the following laws that these
arithmetic operations obey (here we write <B>D</B> for any one
of the five number systems just mentioned, and restrict the quantities
<i>a</I> , <i>b</I> , and <i>c</I> to be quantities from that
system <B>D</B> :
<P>
(i) both <i>a </I>+ <i>b</I> and <i>a </I>&#183; <i>b </I>are
again quantities in the system <B>D</B> ;
<P>
(ii) (associativity) (<i>a </I>+ <i>b</I>) + <i>c</I> = <i>a</I>
+ (<i>b</I> + <i>c</I>) and (<i>a </I>&#183; <i>b</I>) &#183;
<i>c</I> = <i>a </I>&#183; (<i>b </I>&#183; <i>c</I>) ;
<P>
(iii) (commutativity) <i>a + b</I> = <i>b</I> + <i>a</I> and <i>a
</I>&#183; <i>b</I> = <i>b </I>&#183; <i>a</I> ;
<P>
... [<B>Interjection.</B> We digress for a moment to point out
that some familiar, if more complicated, systems of quantities,
for which similar addition and multiplication procedures are available,
need not necessarily obey any more of these laws than, minimally,
the first one (i). Without utterly flogging the point now (its
time will come later), we just remind the reader that in the system
<i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>) of real two-by-two matrices, familiar, perhaps,
from high school algebra, where addition and multiplication are
defined by the rules
<P>
&eacute;<TT><i> a b </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i>
x y </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT> <i>a</I>+<i>x</I>
<i>b</I>+y </TT>&ugrave; &eacute;<TT><i> a b </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT>
</TT>&eacute;<TT><i> x y </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT>
<i>ax</I>+<i>bz ay</I>+<i>bw</I> </TT>&ugrave;
<P>
&ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT> + </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT>
= </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute; , &ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT>
&#215; </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT> = </TT>&ecirc;<TT> <i>
</I></TT>&uacute; ,
<P>
&euml;<TT><i> c d </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i> z w
</I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT> <i>c</I>+<i>z</I> <i>d</I>+<i>w</I>
</TT>&ucirc; &euml;<TT><i> c d </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i>
z w </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT> <i>cx</I>+<i>dz</I> <i>cy</I>+<i>dw</I>
</TT>&ucirc;
<P>
the multiplication does <i>not</I> obey the commutativity law
(iii) (although the addition does): for example,
<P>
&eacute;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i> </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i>
</I>1 0 </TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i> </I>8 0 </TT>&ugrave;
&eacute;<TT><i> </I>1 0 </TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i>
</I>2 2<i> </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i>
</I></TT>&ugrave;
<P>
&ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT> &#215; </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT>
= </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute; , &ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT>
&#215; </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT> = </TT>&ecirc;<TT> <i>
</I></TT>&uacute; .] ...
<P>
&euml;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i>
</I>3 0<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i> </I>8 0 </TT>&ucirc;
&euml;<TT><i> </I>3 0<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i>
</I>2 2<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i> </I>6 6<i>
</I></TT>&ucirc;
<P>
(iv) (neutral elements) there are at least one <i>n</I> in <B>D</B>
for which <i>a</I> + <i>n</I> = <i>a</I> (and <i>n</I> + <i>a</I>
= <i>a ) </I>for all <i>a</I> in <B>D</B> , and at least one quantity
<i>m</I> in <B>D</B> for which <i>a </I>&#183; <i>m</I> = <i>a</I>
(and <i>m </I>&#183; <i>a</I> = <i>a </I>) for all <i>a</I> in
<B>D </B>;
<P>
... [<B>Interjection.</B> We digress again to note, first, that
if there are any neutral elements for addition, there can never
be more than one: for if <i>n</I> and <i>n</I>' seem to be two
such, we have <i>n</I>' = <i>n</I> + <i>n</I>' = <i>n </I>, i.e.,
<i>n</I> = <i>n</I>' .
<P>
Based on the five familiar examples atop this page, it seems reasonable
to reserve the symbol 0 for such additive neutral elements. By
much the same line of thinking, any seeming two multiplicative
neutral elements are also equal -- so that, if there are any,
there's only one -- and it seems reasonable, on the same basis,
to denote them (or rather, <B>it</B>), by the equally familiar
symbol 1 . If the reader is puzzled as to why the second (parenthetical)
equations are included, let us explain that we may, in future,
encounter systems (like <i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>) ) in which commutativity
fails, and we will want our neutral elements to &quot;behave neutrally&quot;
from <i>both</I> sides. (In commutative examples, of course, the
parenthetical equations will just follow from the unparenthesized
ones.) Incidentally, in <i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>) , the neutral elements
0 and 1 are just
<P>
&eacute;<TT><i> </I>0 0<i> </I></TT>&ugrave; &eacute;<TT><i> </I>1
0 </TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>
<P>
<TT>0 = </TT>&ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT> </TT>and 1 =<TT>
</TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT> </TT>, respectively.] ...
<P>
&euml;<TT><i> </I>0 0<i> </I></TT>&ucirc; &euml;<TT><i> </I>0
1<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>
<P>
(v) (distributivity) <i>a</I> &#183; ( <i>b</I> + <i>c</I> ) =
<i>a</I> &#183; <i>b + a</I> &#183; <i>c</I> (and ( <i>a</I> +
<i>b</I> ) &#183; <i>c</I> = <i>a </I>&#183; <i>c</I> <i> + b</I>
&#183; <i>c</I> ) ;
<P>
... [<B>Interjection.</B> The first of the next two laws is valid
in <B>Z</B> , <B>Q</B> ,<B> R</B> , and <B> C</B> (even in <i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>)
), but is violated in <B>N</B> (in fact, <B>Z</B> may be said
to have been invented just so as to &quot;complete&quot; <B>N</B>
to a number system in which that law <i>would</I> be obeyed);
the second one, similarly, though valid in <B>Q</B> ,<B> R</B>
, and <B> C</B> , is violated in <B>Z</B> (and, for that matter,
in <i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>) ) -- in fact, <B>Q</B> may be said to
have been invented, in turn, just so as to complete <B>Z</B> to
a number system in which that law, too, would be obeyed).] ...
<P>
(vi) (additive inverses) for each <i>a</I> in <B>D</B> there are
solutions <i>x</I> , also in <B>D</B> , to the equation(s)
<P>
<i>a </I>+ <i>x</I> = 0 (and <i>x</I> + <i>a</I> = 0 ) ;
<P>
(vii) (multiplicative inverses) for each <i>a</I> in <B>D</B>
, other than <i>a</I> = 0 , there are solutions <i>x</I> , also
in <B>D</B> , to the equation(s)
<P>
<i>a </I>&#183;<i> x </I>=<i> </I>1 (and <i>x</I> &#183; <i>a</I>
= 1 ) .
<P>
... [<B>Interjection.</B> As earlier, the parenthesized equations
are unnecessary (i.e., will follow from the unparenthesized ones)
in the presence of the appropriate commutativity. We include them
for the sake of future reference in any non-commutative situations
that may arise later. As earlier, again, the solutions envisioned
by (vi) and (vii) are unique when they exist. So as not to conflict
with the familiar notation already in use in the number systems
<B>Q</B> ,<B> R</B> , and <B> C</B> , we write -<i>a </I>and <i>a</I>-1
for the additive and multiplicative inverses to a given element
<i>a</I> , when they exist, so that <i>a</I> + (-<i>a</I>) = (-<i>a</I>)
+ <i>a</I> = 0 , and <i>a</I> &#183; (<i>a</I>-1) = (<i>a</I>-1)
&#183; <i>a</I> = 1 , and we write <i>b</I> - <i>a</I> as shorthand
for <i>b</I> + (-<i>a</I>) . It becomes an exercise (Try it!)
to confirm the validity of the expected calculations - (-<i>a</I>)
= <i>a</I> and (<i>a</I>-1)-1 = <i>a</I> . ] ...
<P>
In any system <B>D</B> of quantities having an addition satisfying
laws (i), (ii), and (iv), law (vi), when valid, has the following
consequence:
<P>
(viii) (cancellation for + ) given any quantities <i>a</I> , <i>b</I>
, and <i>c</I> of <B>D</B> , if <i>a</I> + <i>b</I> = <i>a</I>
+ <i>c</I> , then <i>b</I> = <i>c</I> (and if <i>b</I> + <i>a</I>
= <i>c</I> + <i>a</I> , then also <i>b </I>=<i> c</I> ).
<P>
Similarly, in any system <B>D</B> of quantities having addition
and multiplication satisfying laws (i), (ii), and (iv), law (vii),
when valid, has the following consequence:
<P>
(ix) (cancellation for &#183; ) given any quantities <i>a</I>
, <i>b</I> , and <i>c</I> of <B>D</B> , if <i>a</I> &#183; <i>b</I>
= <i>a</I> &#183; <i>c</I> , then either <i>a</I> = 0 or <i>b</I>
= <i>c</I> (and if <i>b</I> &#183; <i>a</I> = <i>c</I> &#183;
<i>a</I> , then again either <i>a</I> = 0 or <i>b </I>=<i> c</I>
).
<P>
<B>Proofs.</B> (vi) =&gt; (viii): If <i>a</I> + <i>b</I> = <i>a</I>
+ <i>c</I> , then
<P>
(-<i>a</I>) + (<i>a</I> + <i>b</I>) = (-<i>a</I>) + (<i>a</I>
+ <i>c</I>) .
<P>
But
<P>
(-<i>a</I>) + (<i>a</I> + <i>b</I>) = ((-<i>a</I>) + <i>a </I>)
+ <i>b</I> = 0 + <i>b</I> = <i>b</I> .
<P>
Similarly,
<P>
(-<i>a</I>) + (<i>a</I> + <i>c</I>) = ((-<i>a</I>) + <i>a </I>)
+ <i>c</I> = 0 + <i>c</I> = <i>c</I> .
<P>
Combining the middle equation, read from right to left, with the
first and last equations, we see <i>b</I> = <i>c</I> .
<P>
(vii) =&gt; (ix): if <i>a</I> &#183; <i>b</I> = <i>a</I> &#183;
<i>c</I> , and if <i>a</I> is not 0 , multiply both sides by <i>a</I>-1
and chug away --
<P>
<i>b</I> = 1 &#183; <i>b</I> = (<i>a</I>-1 &#183; <i>a</I>) &#183;
<i>b</I> = <i>a</I>-1 &#183; (<i>a</I> &#183; <i>b</I>) = <i>a</I>-1
&#183; (<i>a</I> &#183; <i>c</I>) = (<i>a</I>-1 &#183; <i>a</I>)
&#183; <i>c</I> = 1 &#183; <i>c</I> = <i>c</I> .
<P>
It's worth noticing that even though <B>N </B>doesn't satisfy
laws (vi) or (vii), it does satisfy laws (viii) and (ix); and
that <B>Z</B> , likewise, satisfies (ix) even though it doesn't
satisfy (vii). But <i>M</I>2x2(<B>R</B>) , on the other hand,
although it does (like <B>Z</B> ) satisfy laws (vi) and (viii),
does not satisfy laws (vii) or (ix) -- e.g.,
<P>
&eacute;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i> </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i>
</I>1 0 </TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i> </I>8 0 </TT>&ugrave;
&eacute;<TT><i> </I>2 2 </TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>&eacute;<TT><i>
</I>2 0<i> </I></TT>&ugrave;<TT> </TT>
<P>
&ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT> &#215; </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT>
= </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute;<TT> = </TT>&ecirc;<TT><i> </I></TT>&uacute;<TT>
&#215; </TT>&ecirc;<TT> </TT>&uacute; . &euml;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i>
</I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i> </I>3 0<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT>
</TT>&euml;<TT><i> </I>8 0 </TT>&ucirc; &euml;<TT><i> </I>2 2<i>
</I></TT>&ucirc;<TT> </TT>&euml;<TT><i> </I>2 0<i> </I></TT>&ucirc;<TT>
</TT>
</BODY>

