<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Well - Ordering</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><H1>Well - Ordering</H1></CENTER>
<iMG SRC="rip.gif">
<P>
<B>Axiom:</B>  If X is a subset of Z which is not empty and has a lower bound, then X has a least member. 
<P>
The above axiom is known as the well - ordering axiom.  An excellent way to intuitively grasp the meaning of the well - ordering axiom is to picture a game in which two individuals alternately pick members of a set, X.  The only rule of the game is that each individual has to select an element that is in X and is less than the element that was selected by the previous player.  Eventually, if someone wins the game, by picking a member of X which has no element smaller than the most recently chosen element, the set has a least element and is well - oredered.  If the game goes on forever, nobody wins and there is no least element.  Such a set, X, is not well- oredered.
<P>
This property may seem obvious, but it is not always simple.  There are some sets, X, which might have a lower bound, but no least element.  An excellent example of this is 
(n+1)/n for all n &gt;= 2.  This set has a lower bound, 1, but it does not have a least element.  If this were the set, X, used for the game, the game would go on forever and neither player could win.  Each player would choose fractions that get closer and closer to 1 without ever reaching it.  This set is therefore not well - ordered. <a href="ref.html">(Biggs)</a>   
<P>
<iMG SRC="rip.gif">
<P>
<P>
We can use the well - ordered principle to prove theorems, such as:
<P>
<B>Theorem:</B>  There is no intereger between 0 and 1.
<P>
Here, we will prove this theorem using an indirect proof.  If there was such an interger, r, then 0 &lt; r &lt; 1, where r is a non - empty set.  By the well - ordering priciple, there is a least element, m,  in r, such that  0 &lt; m &lt; 1.  We can then proceed by multiplying all sides of the inequalities by m, producing:  0 &lt; m(m) &lt; m.  Thus, m(m) is another element in r, that is less than the least element in r, m.  This, of course, is a contradiction and therefore there is no element m and r is the empty set.  This is an indirect proof that establishes the above theorem.  It shows the flexibility of the well ordering axiom. <a href="ref.html">(Birkhoff & MacLane)</a>
<P>
<B>Theorem:</B>  A set S of positive intergers which includes 1, and which includes n + 1 whenever it includes n, includes every positive interger.  In order to prove that S contains every positive intereger, we can prove that S', consisting of those positive intergers not in S, is empty.  If S' were not empty, it would have a least element.  This is due to the Well Ordering Principal which states that the positive intergers are well - ordered.  Let the least element in S' be represented by q.  We know that q does not equal 1 because of our hypothesis.  Therefore, q &gt; 1 and q - 1 &gt; 0.  This means that  q - 1 &lt; q, and because q is the least element in S',  q - 1  must be in S.  Our hypothesis would lead us to believe that (q - 1) + 1 = q  is in S as well.  The fact that q is in S and not S' is a contradiction and therefore the theorem is proven. <a href="ref.html">(Birkhoff & MacLane)</a> 
<P>
<iMG SRC="rip.gif">
<P>
<P>
<H2>Exercises involving the Well - Ordered Axiom</H2>
<B>1.</B>  Which of the following sets are well - ordered?
<PRE>
     a) all odd positive integers
     b) all even negative integers
     c) all integers greater than -7
     d) all  odd integers greater than 249 <a href="ref.html">(Birkhoff & MacLane)</a>
     e) n is in N: n = 110 - 17m <a href="ref.html">(Polimeni & Joseph)</a>
     f) x is in Z: x2 &lt;= 16 <a href="ref.html">(Biggs)</a> 
</PRE>
<P>
<B>2.</B>  Prove that a set of integers which contains  -1000, and contains  x + 1, when it contains x, contains all of the positive integers. <a href="ref.html">(Birkhoff and MacLane)</a>
<P>
<iMG SRC="rip.gif">
<P>
<P>
<H2>Solutions to Exercises</H2>
<B>1.</B>
<PRE>
     a) well - ordered,  least element is 1.
     b) not well - ordered,  no least element.
     c) well - ordered, least element is -6.
     d) well - ordered, least element is 251.
     e) well - ordered, least element is 8.
        When m = 6,  n = 110 - (17)(6) = 110 - 102 = 8
     f) well - ordered, least element is -4.  
</PRE>
<P>
<B>2.</B>  If -1000 is in S, (-1000 +1) is in S by definition. Let the set S' consist of all positive integers not in S.  Let x be in S' and let x be the least element of S'.  Therefore, (x - 1) is not in S' and is in S.  Then ((x-1) + 1) is also in S by definition.  This is a contradiction and S contains all positive integers.
<P>
<P>
<P>
