<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Wesuser">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>Induction and Well-Orderedness</H1>

<P>
In class we have seen that from the well-ordering principle (see
below) for the system <B>N</B> of natural numbers one may infer
both the induction principle (labeled (4) on the board)
<P>
If a collection <i>S</I> of natural numbers contains the number
0 , and if, regardless what the number <i>n</I> may be, it contains
the number <i>n</I> + 1 whenever it contains the number <i>n</I>
, then <i>S</I> = <B>N</B> 
<P>
and (from it in turn) that variant thereof (labeled (4') on the
board) stating
<P>
If a collection <i>S</I> of natural numbers contains the number
<i>k</I> whenever all natural numbers <i>n</I> that satisfy <i>n</I>
&lt; <i>k</I> are included in <i>S</I> , then <i>S</I> = <B>N</B>
.
<P>
The well-ordering principle itself (wo) states:
<P>
If a collection <i>S</I> of natural numbers contains any numbers
at all (i.e., is not totally empty), then <i>S</I> contains a
number <i>n</I> that is smallest among all the numbers belonging
to <i>S</I> .
<P>
<B>Exercise.</B> Develop a line of reasoning by which the well-ordering
principle just stated can be seen to be a consequence of one of
the induction principles stated above.
<P>
[Hint: suppose you are faced with what claims to be a counterexample
to the well-ordering principle, i.e., that you are confronted
with a set <i>S</I> for which there is <i>no</I> natural number
<i>n</I> that is a least member of <i>S</I> . Let <i>S'</I> stand
for the set of all natural numbers <i>n</I> that are omitted from
<i>S</I> . Use (4') to show <i>S'</I> = <B>N</B> , so that <i>S</I>
must in fact be empty, and therefore not a counterexample to (wo)
at all.]
</BODY>

</HTML>
