<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Principle of Finite Induction</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><H1>The Principle of Finite Induction</H1></CENTER>
<P>
The Principle of Finite Induction is a powerful tool used to prove many elementary theorems and ideas in modern algebra.  In class we saw the principle of finite induction used to prove the well-ordering principle.  This proof will reviewed later.  The following few paragraphs will attempt to cover four areas concerning induction.  They will <a href="#PartOne">(1)</a> outline the theory behind the principle of finite induction, <a href="#PartTwo">(2)</a> prove that the principle in fact holds, <a href="#PartThree">(3)</a> give an example of the principle of finite induction at work, and <a href="#PartFour">(4)</a> suggest and give the solutions to problems found in the first chapter of <a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff and MacLane's: Survey of Modern Algebra.</a><P>
<P>

<a name="PartOne">
<CENTER><H2>Part One</H2></CENTER>
The Principle of Finite Induction is used to prove fundamental ideas of modern algebra.  The principle works as follows.  For a subset S of natural numbers (from now on abbreviated N), let there be a function p(n) associated with each value n that is found in S.  Let p(n) be either true or false.  If p(0) is found to be true, and, for every q in which p(q) is true then p(q+1) is also true, then p(n) is true for all n.  Thus, if we can show that p(0) is true and that p(q+1) is true when p(q) is assumed to be true, then we know that p(n) is true for all n.  The simplicity behind this principle is what makes it so easy and useful.
<P>
<P>

<a name="PartTwo">
<CENTER><H2>Part Two</H2></CENTER>
To prove the principle of finite induction, the following statement must be proven true:
<P>
When S is a subset of N, with 0 as a member of S, and  (n+1) as a member of S when n is a member of S, then the S=N.
<P>
<B>Proof:</B>
<P>
Assume S to be a subset of N with 0 as a member of S and (n+1) as a member of S when n is also a member of S, such that S does not equal N.  Thus, there are values in N that are not in S.  Let T be the set of values of N that are excluded from set S.
<P>
Because S does not equal N, there must be some number p in T that acts as a least element.  Thus, p is not in set S.  All natural numbers smaller than p must be in set S, though, because p is the smallest natural number excluded from set S.  What values could p possibly have?
<P>
p cannot be 0 by hypothesis.  Also, p cannot be 1 because (n+1) is S, and (0+1)=1.  So, p must be greater than 1.  Thus, (p-1) must be a member of S.  But, (p-1)+1 must also be in S.  (p-1)+1=p, though, which says that p must be in S.  This creates a contradiction that we cannot allow.
<P>
Our original hypothesis is shown to have been faulty.  When S is a subset of N with 0 as a member of S and (n+1) as a member of S when n is a member of S, then S=N, and the principle of finite induction holds.  Q.E.D.
<P>
<P>

<a name="PartThree">
<CENTER><H2>Part Three</H2></CENTER>
An example where the principle of finite induction was used was given both in class and on the quiz given on October 2, 1995.
<P>
<B>Example Problem:</B>
<P>
Using these induction principles:
<P>
<a name="Prop1">
<B>i)</B> If a collection S of natural numbers contains the number 0, and if, regardless what the number n may be, it contains the number (n+1) whenever it contains the number n, then S=N.
<P>
<a name="Prop2">
<B>ii)</B> If a collection S of natural numbers contains the number k whenever all natural numbers n that satisfy n (less than) k are included, then S=N.
<P>
. . .  develop a line of reasoning by which the following statement concerning the well-ordering principle can be seen to be a consequence of one of the two induction principles above:
<P>
If a collection of S of natural numbers contains any numbers at all (i.e. is not totally empty), then S contains a number n that is smallest among all the numbers belonging to S.  
<P>
<P>
<B>Example Solution:</B> (proposed by F.E.J. Linton)
<P>
Suppose there were a set S for which no natural number n is a least member of S.  Where S' stands for the set of all natural numbers that are omitted from S, the natural number 0 must be omitted from S (otherwise it would be the least number in S), and hence, is must be in S'.  Thus, the set S' is not empty.
<P>
Since 0 is in S', where is 1?  Because any number in S is non-zero, all numbers in S (if any) must be greater than or equal to 1.  We must omit 1 from S because, if not omitted, it would be a least element in S.  Thus, 1 also belongs to S'.  More generally, if k is a natural number for which we happen to know that whatever natural numbers there may be that are less then k all belong to S', then we know that no natural number less than k can belong to S, and so k itself, were it to belong to S, would be the least number in S.  So (S not containing any least number) k too must belong to S'.
<P>
Thus, S' fulfills the "k is in S' whenever all numbers less than k are in S' " condition specified in <a href="#Prop2">(ii)</a>.  So, according to <a href="#Prop2">(ii)</a>, as applied to this set of numbers S', we may infer that S'=N.  But this in turn means that the original set S must be empty.  In effect, we have shown that from the assumption that S contains no smallest number we can infer that S contains no numbers at all.  If S does contain any numbers at all, it must contain a smallest one, i.e., we have derived the statement from proposition <a href="#Prop2">(ii)</a>.  Q.E.D.
<P>
<P>

<a name="PartFour">
<CENTER><H2>Part Four</H2></CENTER>
Recommended problems involving the principle of finite induction can be found in section 5 of chapter 1 in <a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff and MacLane's: Survey of Modern Algebra.</a>  The questions worth reviewing are 1, 2, and 5.  The following solutions are not 100 percent correct.
<P>
<P>
<B>1. a)</B>  (a' )' can be rewritten as (a' ) (a' )  . . .  (a' ) where there are n factors of (a' ).  Each (a' ) can be rewritten as a a . . . a with m factors of a.  Thus, (a' )'=a a a . . .  a with (mn) factors of a.  That is equivalent to a''.  
<P>
Thus, (a' )  = a' = a a a . . . a with m factors.  If we assume (a' )'  to be true, then we need to show that (a' )'   is true.  (a' )'  = (a' )'  (a' )  , by law four on page 12 of <a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff & MacLane</a>.  a'   a'= a'    .  Q.E.D.
<P>
<B>b)</B>  (ab)' = ab.  If we assume that (ab)'  = a' b', we need to show that (ab)'  = a'   b'   .  (ab)'   = (ab)'  (ab)' = a' b' ab = a'  a b'  b .  By law 6 on page 12 of <a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff & MacLane</a>, (a'  a) (b'  b)= a'   b'   .  Q.E.D.
<P>
<B>c)</B>  1' =1.  if we assume 1' =1, it is enough to show that 1'   =1.  By postulate 7 on page 2 of <a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff & MacLane</a>,  1'   =1'  1' = 1' .  Also, 1'  =1, so, 1'   =1' .  Q.E.D.
<P>
<P>
<B>2.</B>  When n=1, 1(1+1)/2 =1, which is the expected result.  If we assume n(n+1)/2 to be true, then it is enough to show that the equation works when (n+1) is the input.  1+2+ . . . + n + (n+1)= n(n+1)/2 + (n+1).  Expanding gives:  (n' +3n+2)/2.  This can be factored as follows:  (n+1)((n+1) +1)/2 = 1+2+3+ . . . + (n+1).  Q.E.D.
<P>
<P>
<B>5. a)</B>  for n=1 the formula yields:  2(3)/6=1, which is the expected result.  If we assume that the formula works for n, the principle of induction says it will be good enough to show that (n+1) works, also.  1+4+9+ . . . + n'+ (n+1)'= (n(n+1)(2n+1))/6 + (n+1)'  .  Simplifying gives:  (2n  + 9n  + 13n +6)/6.  Factoring gives:  ((n+1)((n+1)+1)(2(n+1)+1))/6= 1+4+9+ . . . + (n+1)'. Q.E.D.
<P>
<B>b)</B>  for n=1, ((1(1+1))/2)=1, which is the expected result.  Assuming that the formula works for n, the principle of finite induction says that it will be good enough to show that the formula works for (n+1).  1+8+27+ . . . + (n+1)' = (n(n+1)/2) + (n+1)'  .  This simplifies to:  (n'  + 6n'  +  13n'  + 12n +  4)/4.  Factoring gives:  ((n+1)((n+1)+1)/2)= 1+ 8+27+ . . . + (n+1)'  .  Q.E.D. 

</BODY>
