</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Integers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><H1>Integers</H1></CENTER>
<P>
The set of numbers known as integers could be seen as a solution to the problems which arise in the natural number set.  It is about second grade when the concept of integers is generally introduced.  One could look at it from the perspective of a child who, at lunch, borrows a sandwich from another second grader.  The next week the child is asked to repay his debt, and although both children have an intuitive sense of what this means, neither can express the debt on paper.  This is where the integers are introduced.  
<P>
Integers encompass all numbers which are included in the natural number set, but also encompass all of the negative whole numbers as well.  Thus numbers such as 0, 1, 2, 3 are in the set of integers, but now -1, -2, -3 are also included in the set.  In fact, for every positive number in the set of integers there is also a number equal in value, but opposite in sign.  Integers, like natural numbers, do not include fraction such as 1/4.  The formal definition of integers could be stated as:
<P>
Z= {. . .-1001, -1000, . . .-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, . . . 1000, 1001, . . .}-
<P>
The collection of all such whole numbers, positive, negative or zero.
<P>
Much like the natural numbers, the integers have certain physical features to which it adheres.  In fact, many of its features are the same as the natural numbers.  Like the natural numbers, one number from the set is always greater than or equal to another number from the set.  The integers also fulfill some mathematical operations.  The sum of any two integers will always be another integer, also the product of any two integers will be another integer.  However, unlike the natural numbers, subtraction does hold for the integers, such that any integer subtracted from another integer will yield another integer.   Also unlike the natural numbers, for the integers, an integer cannot always be raised to the power of another integer, e.g.    2^-2=1/4, which is quite obviously not an integer.  Division does not hold for the integers for the same reason that a fractional answer, i.e. 2/5, is possible.
<P>
The question now becomes, Is the integer set an integral domain?  One would guess so, due to both the likeness in names as well as the fact that integers were invented to solve the problem of the natural numbers.  However we still must prove it, and the set will only be an integral domain if multiplication and addition hold for the set (which they do) and each of nine mathematical postulates hold for the set (which will be examined now).
<P>
<B>I. Closure:</B> This has already been examined, and the set does have closure.
<P>
<B>II. Uniqueness:</B> If a=a' and b=b' the a+b=a'+b' and ab=a'b'.  This should be fairly obvious for the set since there is only one of each number in the set then if a=a' and b=b' then clearly a+b=x and a'+b'=x and since x=x then a+b=a'+b'.  The same method holds for multiplication.  
<P>
<B>III. Commutative Laws:</B> a+b=b+a and ab=ba.  Order simply does not matter in the + and x of the integer set.  Common sense dictates that 2+3=3+2 since they both equal 5.  The same is true of multiplication.  (Or one could use this algebraic which works equally well for + and x)
<PRE>
          a+b=b+a             Given
          x=b+a               Let a+b=x
          x-a=b               Subtracting a from both sides
          a+b-a=b             Substituting back in for x
          b=b                 Simple algebra      
                         Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<B>IV. Associative Laws:</B> a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c and a(bc)=(ab)c.  Much like the reasoning behind the commutative law, the associative law works under the same assumption that the order of + or x does not really matter.  If one has three elements a, b, and c, within the sum of the three will be the same regardless of the order of +.  (Or I could use this algebraic argument which works equally well for both + and x)
<PRE>
         a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c      Given
         a+x=y+c              Let b+c=x and a+b=y
         a-c=y-x              Subtracting c and x from both sides
         a-c=(a+b)-(b+c)      Substituting back for x and y
         a-c=a-c              Distributive Law
                         Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<B>V. Distributive law:</B> a(b+c)=ab+ac.  One could look at the distributive law from one of two angles.  Either it could be seen from the logical standpoint that since order of operation in the set does not matter, then the distributive law clearly holds.  Or one can look at the proof of the distributive law from an algebraic point of view:
<PRE>
         a(b+c)=ab+ac         Given 
         ax=ab+ac if          Let b+c=x
         0=ab+ac-ax           You subtract ax from both sides you get
         0=a(b+c-x)           Since a is a common factor of all three
         0=a[b+c-(b+c)]       Substituting b+c back in for x
         0=a(0)               From uniqueness b+c=b+c
         0=0                  Since 0 time anything equals 0
                         Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<B>VI. Zero:</B> a+0=a.  The reason why this rule holds for the set is inherent within the number 0.  0 is a neutral element, thus it does not alter the number to which it is added, thus any number a when added to zero would simply be the number a.
<P>
<B>VII. Unity:</B> (a)(1)=a.  Once again this holds simply because of the fact that 1 is, by its nature, a neutral element for multiplication.  Thus whenever 1 in multiplied by any other number from the set, the answer will simply be the number.
<P>
Note: Because of the simplicity of postulates VI and VII and also the fact that the postulates are analogous, 0 and 1 are referred to as "identity elements" for addition and multiplication respectively. <a href="ref.htm">(Birkhoff and MacLane)</a>
<P>
<B>VIII. Additive Inverse:</B> For each a in set D, a+x=0 has a solution x in D.  This was where the natural number set failed.  But here the integers succeed and the reason is simply due to the construction of the set.  Since the set of integers consist of all whole numbers, positive or negative, then for every a, there must be -a.  Thus when -a is substituted in for x,the additive inverse postulate holds, for a+(-a)=0.
<P>
<B>IX. Cancellation Law:</B> If c does not =0 and ca=cb, then a=b. This can be quite easily  proven algebraically:
<PRE>
         ca=cb                Given
         0=cb-ca              Subtracting ca from both sides
         0=c(b-a)             Using distributive law
         0=b-a                Since c does not =0 and / both sides by c
         a=b                  Adding a to both side
                        Q.E.D.
</PRE>
After testing the integers it becomes clear that the set of intergers is actually an integral domain.
</DOC>
