<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Natural Numbers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><H1>Natural Numbers</H1></CENTER>
<P>
When one remembers back to first grade and the first steps of one's mathematical training, the first mathematical concept learned was how to count.  0, 1, 2, 3, 4, etc. are the building blocks of our current mathematical knowledge.  In first grade a child does not know this, but those numbers being counted actually comprise the natural number set which is the oldest and most basic number set.
<P>
Natural numbers could be defined as whole integers without negative numbers.  0, 1, 2, and so forth are all natural numbers; however, -1, -2, -3, and the kind are not natural numbers.  The set of natural number does not include fractions, thus 1/4 is not a natural number.  Thus the formal definition of the natural number set could be stated as:
<P>
N = {0, 1, 2, 3, . . ., 1000, 1001, . . .} - the collection of all such whole, positive, "natural" numbers.
<P>
The natural number set has certain physical features to which it adheres.  The first is that one number in the set is always greater than or equal to another number in the set.  The natural number set also fulfills some mathematical functions.  The sum of any two numbers within the set will always be another number within the set.  The product of any two numbers within the set will always be another number within the set.  Finally, one natural number raised to the power of another natural number will always be a natural number.  However, the natural number set does not always fulfill the subtraction and division functions, for 3-5 does not have an answer from within the set, as well 3/5 does not have an answer from within the set.
<P>
The question now becomes, Is the natural number set an integral domain?  The set will only be an integral domain if multiplication and addition hold for the set (which they do) and each of nine mathematical postulates hold for the set (which will be examined now).
<P>
<B>I. Closure:</B> This has already been examined, and the set does have closure.
<P>
<B>II. Uniqueness:</B> If a=a' and b=b' the a+b=a'+b' and ab=a'b'.  This should be fairly obvious for the set since there is only one of each number in the set then if a=a' and b=b' then clearly a+b=x and a'+b'=x and since x=x then a+b=a'+b'.  The same method holds for multiplication.  
<P>
<B>III. Commutative Laws:</B> a+b=b+a and ab=ba.  Order simply does not matter in the + and x of the natural number set.  Common sense dictates that 2+3=3+2 since they both equal 5.  The same is true of multiplication.  (Or I could use this algebraic which works equally well for + and x) 
<PRE>
          a+b=b+a            Given
          x=b+a              Let a+b=x
          x-a=b              Subtracting a from both sides
          a+b-a=b            Substituting back in for x
          b=b                Simple algebra      
                    Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<P>
<B>IV. Associative Laws:</B> a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c and a(bc)=(ab)c.  Much like the reasoning behind the commutative law, the associative law works under the same assumption that the order of + or x does not really matter.  If one has three elements a, b, and c, within the sum of the three will be the same regardless of the order of +.  (Or I could use this algebraic argument which works equally well for both + and x)
<PRE>
          a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c    Given
          a+x=y+c            Let b+c=x and a+b=y
          a-c=y-x            Subtracting c and x from both sides
          a-c=(a+b)-(b+c)    Substituting back for x and y
          a-c=a-c            Distributive Law
                    Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<P>
<B>V. Distributive law:</B> a(b+c)=ab+ac.  One could look at the distributive law from one of two angles.  Either it could be seen from the logical standpoint that since order of operation in the set does not matter, then the distributive law clearly holds.  Or one can look at the proof of the distributive law from an algebraic point of view:
<PRE>
          a(b+c)=ab+ac       Given 
          ax=ab+ac if        Let b+c=x
          0=ab+ac-ax         You subtract ax from both sides you get
          0=a(b+c-x)         Since a is a common factor of all three
          0=a[b+c-(b+c)]     Substituting b+c back in for x
          0=a(0)             From uniqueness b+c=b+c
          0=0                Since 0 time anything equals 0
                    Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<P>
<B>VI. Zero:</B> a+0=a.  The reason why this rule holds for the set is inherent within the number 0.  0 is a neutral element, thus it does not alter the number to which it is added, thus any number a when added to zero would simply be the number a.
<P>
<B>VII. Unity:</B> (a)(1)=a.  Once again this holds simply because of the fact that 1 is, by its nature, a neutral element for multiplication.  Thus whenever 1 in multiplied by any other number from the set, the answer will simply be the number.
<P>
Note: Because of the simplicity of postulates VI and VII and also the fact that the postulates are analogous, 0 and 1 are referred to as "identity elements" for addition and multiplication respectively. (<a href="ref.htm">Birkhoff and MacLane</a>)?
<P>
<B>VIII. Additive Inverse:</B> For each a in set D, a+x=0 has a solution x in D.  This is where the natural number set breaks down, for it fails to fulfill this postulate.  This is fairly obvious, since there are no negative numbers within the natural number set, then 1+x=0 does not have a solution.
<P>
<B>IX. Cancellation Law:</B> If c does not =0 and ca=cb, then a=b. This can be quite easily proven algebraically:
<PRE>
          ca=cb              Given
          0=cb-ca            Subtracting ca from both sides
          0=c(b-a)           Using distributive law
          0=b-a              Since c does not =0 and / both sides by c
          a=b                Adding a to both side
                    Q.E.D.
</PRE>
<P>
<P>
<P>
After testing the natural number set with each of the nine postulates, it is clear that the natural number set is not an integral domain.  This is because of the fact that the set fails the additive inverse postulate.  However, there is another set of numbers which corrects this problem: the <a href="integers.htm">integers</a>.
</BODY>
</HTML>

</DOC>
