<A NAME="3" HREF="#4"><STRONG>Summary of Objectives and Approach.</STRONG></A><P>

<!Comment: following is an ordered list >
<!Comment: each new item in the list starts with a 'LI' at the left margin >

<UL>
 To develop mathematical foundations and techniques for exploiting the calculus
of relations as a programming discipline, and as a framework for

<UL>
<LI> - Extending and providing categorical semantics for declarative
programming with constraints.<p>  

<LI> - Developing and extending the  foundations of logic programming.
<p>  

<LI> - Exploring applications to non-determinism and computing with partial
information. <p> 
</UL>


   
<LI> To develop a theory of relational computation: determine the
computational strength and semantics of different relational calculi for
computation.  Explore  denotational, operational and
realizability semantics for such disciplines. Address such 
questions as: which classes of functions are computable in the different
calculi, how does one capture just total, feasible or typable
computations through restrictions of the relational calculi, etc.  

<LI> Study relational extensions of realizability, type hierarchies,
and logical relation models. Study the relational counterpart of
lambda-definablity questions.

<LI> To develop Category-theoretic foundations of the syntax and semantics of 
logic programming with constraints, functions and different formal systems.

<LI> To develop relational programming with partial information in the
form of <em> constraints</em>, i.e.,  with
relational inputs and outputs. To develop a systematic
approach to high-level program optimization via transformations of relational
programs by rewriting at the relational level, and studying  the
relevant confluence and Church Rosser properties.
 
To study equational and Horn presentations of relational theories with
transitive closure and other recursive operators. Also:

<LI> To bring out the combinatory nature of
database and logic programming (Prolog and generalizations), and especially
constraint logic programming as relational programming languages. Such
languages can be formalized in terms of extensions (with recursive combinators)
of variable free relational calculi in the  general
framework of Peter Freyd's Division Allegories and the higher order  Division
and Power Allegories. 

<LI> To define and study the internal logic of categories suitable for constraint handling and relational programming, in particular, Cartesian, distributive categories and various types of allegories.

<LI> To provide a natural declarative extension of typed,
polymorphic functional programming, that integrates the semantics of both
declarative and functional paradigms.
To explore further the use of denotational, PERs and other categorical
models developed by the first author and
other researchers for type theories and polymorphism 
to include declarative and relational languages.
</UL>


<P> <HR> <P>


<A NAME="4" HREF="#5"><STRONG>Detailed Summary of Technical Progress.</STRONG></A><P>

<!Comment: following is an ordered list >
<!Comment: each new item in the list starts with a 'LI' at the left margin >

<UL>
   
<H2>Categorical Logic Programming</H2>
<H3>Freyd-Finkelstein-Lipton</H3>
In <i>"Logic Programming Tau categories" </I> we build on earlier
dissertation work by Stacy Finkelstein  on  <i>Tau categories: </I>
categories with canonical structure first introduced by Freyd in the
1970's, to formalize a categorical syntax and semantics for a very
general notion of logic programming with constraints. This work also
draws on earlier work by Asperti-Martini and Burtsall-Rydehard.

In her dissertation, Finkelstein defined the notion of a logic
programming category of constraints (a category with finite
products, certain limits and tau-structure) over which a program
predicates are defined as monics and within which a categorical notion
of tau-SLD resolution is formalized. In our present work we have defined a
semantics generalizing the Kowalski- Van Emden fixed point operator to
obtain a non-ground functorial semantics which is sound and complete
for tau SLD resolution over arbitrary categories with finite products
(including a terminartor). Such categories, equipped with an
interpretation of logic, are called LP-categories. We define an
abstract notion of program as a (finite) collection of diagrams of a
certain type in LP-categories C[X] obtained by adjoining indeterminate
monics (predicates) of the appropriate types  to the base LP-category
C. <p>

<B>Semantics</B> Fix an LP category C.  We consider the category
<i>LC-Struct</I> of L-C-structures: sub-categories of the Yoneda category
Set^C^op that extend the interpretation of terms in C to include
interpretations of all predicates in the language L.  We define a
continuous (filtered-colimit-preserving) endofunctor T(P,C) on<i>
LC-Struct</I>. Countable iteration T* of  T(P,C) on C produces an intial
model. In fact T* is a monad from <i>LC-Struct</I> to the 
subcategory <i>Mod(P)</I> of models of <i>P</I>. 

By varying  <i>P</I> and the base category C we are studying variants
of T which capture more general notions (such as Hereditarily Harrop) 
logic programming, and which propagate constraints. By extending T to
take as input a search strategy we are able to define a quite general
denotational semantics to model the computational, intensional
behavior of logic programs.



<H2>Allegories</H2>
<H3>Freyd</H3>
Most of my work in computing with relations has been in developing a
correspondence between structural properties of allegories and different features of
relational computing in two main areas: the Logic of Cartesian
Categories and Hardware Specification Categories. 
 I have also been working with the co-PI on developing a relational
programming language based on rewriting terms in distributive and division
allegories endowed with certain operations (e.g. transitive
closure). A prototype implementation based on earlier work by Lipton
and Broome is described in the  <A HREF="#6"> Software Prototypes.</A> section
below.

<H2>The Logic of Cartesian Categories</H2>
<H3>Freyd-Lipton</H3>
As has been understood since the 60's, the syntax that corresponds to 
categories with products is the syntax of equational (many-sorted) 
algebraic theories.  Since that time many other such correspondences
have been established. The syntax corresponding to logoi, for 
example, is first-order logic. But a curious gap has
remained: what is the syntax corresponding to cartesian categories,
that is, categories with finite limits. Perhaps no kind of category is more
frequently encountered in mathematics.

The answer is, essentially, the logic of ``unique existential quantification".
The assertions allowed by this logic are of the following sort: we allow free
formulas formed as conjunctions of primitive predicates and equality; an 
assertion is a pair of such formulas  <i>P</I>  and  <i>Q</I>   written thusly:

                          P ue> Q

the intended interpretation (informally) of which is that for every instantiation of the
variables in  P  (for which  P  holds) there is unique instantiation of the 
remaining variables (for which  Q  holds).  Hence if all variables
in  Q  also appear in  P  this is the usual notion of implication. If, on
the other hand, there are variables in  Q  that don't appear in  P, then
the assertion is existential.  Not just existential: the elements whose
existence is being asserted are unique.
The rules of inference for this logic are sufficiently complicated to make it 
seem that cartesian categories were invented precisely because the traditional 
syntactical methods were too cumbersome for mathematicians to handle. But
they are not too complicated for a machine.
Among the theories that appear as special cases of this syntax are ``essentially
algebraic theories" and almost every theory of ``categories with structure". 
Perhaps the most important single case is the theory of cartesian categories.
(Note that categories with products are most definitely not a special case of
equational algebraic theories.)

The logic of Cartesian and distributive categories provides a new
syntax for logic programming and constraints which is quite general,
Lipton and I are currently studying the implementation of a logic
programming language based on this syntax.


<H2>Non-deterministic Relational Semantics for typed calculi</H2>
<H3>Lipton-Odonnell</H3>
We introduce a new semantics for constructive
reasoning, called <EM> relational realizability</EM> 
We prove soundness of the Heyting calculus for relational
realizability, and conjecture that there is a constructive choice-free
proof of completeness. In this respect, relational realizability
improves the metamathematical constructivity of Lauchli
realizability (which uses choice in two crucial ways to prove
completeness) in the same sort of way Beth semantics improves Kripke
semantics. Our model is a constructive relational analogue of the <EM> Full type
hierarchy </EM> or set-theoretic model of typed lambda calculus which
extends to Martin-Loef type theory with one universe. The underlying
domain is an allegory whose hom-sets (A,B) consist of entire relations
on AxB. Realizers are <B>finite sets</B> of individuals at each <B>kind</B> which
area type-invariant under a family permutations. These finite sents
and the way permutations act on them represent non-deterministic
approximations to values in the semantics. In the interests of
developing a fully constructive semantics, careful attention has been
given to the formulation of relation and finite set, essentially along
the lines of IZF.


<H2>Combinatory Logic Programming</H2>
<H3>Lipton-Broome</H3>

We define a combinatory relational calculus 
based on a (Allegory-theoretic) variant of the <EM> Relation Algebra</EM> formalism 
(developed by Tarski-Givant, and in more general form by Freyd and others)
which extends traditional database query formalisms in a number of ways. 
It is a variable-free calculus for rewriting relation expressions built up
from ground relations using union, intersection, complementation, composition 
and a fixed point operator. The language extends conventional Horn-clause
programming with constraints (e.g.  constructive 
negation) by permitting queries and outputs to be relation
expressions. We also define  
an associated relational programming language <TT>Ralog </TT>
which combines rewriting in the calculus with a quantifier-elimination 
algorithm due to Mal'cev. The algorithm is used to translate reduced relation
expressions in the calculus  into two-quantifier formulas, which
constitute the printed output of the language.The relational calculi and 
programming language discussed in this paper (\rl) arose from an attempt to
abstract the {\em second order\/} or pure relational content of logic 
programs as objects that bind relation variables and formally
define relations somewhat the way lambda terms 
formally define functions.
There are several benefits to be gained from such an attempt: 
to combine the declarative transparency and reversibility  
of logic programming with some of the features
of functional programming languages, and to open
the way for a new denotational treatment of the semantics of declarative
programming. In this paper we use the relation algebra formalism as an
executable algebra of programs, somewhat in the Backus tradition
to ``liberate logic programming from the von Neumann style.''
Another objective has been to make constraint manipulation and some
features of control more transparent and
declarative by finding a unified calculus which
express constraints, program transformation, evaluation and the logic
program itself. 

<H2>Relational Rewriting</H2>
<H3>Freyd-Lipton-Dougherty</H3>
We are studying rewriting systems for relational terms which
formalize reasoning over different allegories. Rewriting in allegories
with higher order structure (e.g power allegories) offers the
possibility of formalizing a very expressive declarative programming 
language in which evaluation includes program transformation and
optimization. We are planning to implement a prototype using the
rewriting tools developed by Dougherty and his students in the
Wesleyan Rewriting Project.
</OL>

