<html>

<head>
<TITLE>Links to Chesterton's Works</TITLE>
</head>

<body>

<H1>Chesterton's Works on the Web</H1>


I've assembled a non-representative sample of Chesterton here:
<UL>
<LI>A poem:  "<A HREF = "songs.html">Songs of Education III</A>"
<LI>An essay:  "<A HREF = "american.html">On American Morals</A>"
<LI>A Father Brown story:  "<A HREF = "oracle.html">The Oracle of the Dog</A>"
</UL>

There is much, much more available:
<UL>
<LI>A few more poems can be found in the electronic bowels of <A HREF = "http://www.columbia.edu/acis/bartleby/mbp/49.html">Bartleby Library</A> but if your browser is finicky click <A HREF = "poems.html">here</A> instead.
<li>Chesterton's collected works are being published by <A HREF = "http://www.ignatius.com/books/collgkc.htm">Ignatius Press</A>.
<LI>The clearinghouse for Chesterton works online is <A HREF = "http://ws-mj3.dur.ac.uk/gkc/books/index.html">Martin Ward's G. K. Chesterton Page</A>.
<LI>In the U.S., one can find a few books online at <A HREF = "http://ccel.wheaton.edu/chesterton/">Wheaton College</A> and <A HREF = "ftp://kuyper.cs.pitt.edu/ebooks/HTML/chesterton/">The University of Pittburgh</A>.
</ul>

The latter are:  <em>The Innocence of Father Brown</em> and <em>The Wisdom of Father Brown</em> two collections of Father Brown mysteries; the novels <em>The Club of Queer Trades</em> and <em>The Man Who Was Thursday</em>; <em>Heretics</em>, a collection of essays against the iconoclasts of the day and <em>Orthodoxy</em>, which claims to be both a sequel to <em>Heretics</em> and an <em>Apologia pro vita sua</em>.


<p>
Of the Chesterton online, I can recommend only <em>Heretics</em> and <A HREF = "http://ws-mj3.dur.ac.uk/gkc/books/manalive.txt"><em>Manalive</em></A>.  The orthodox will enjoy <em>Orthodoxy</em>, but works of more general appeal are, strangely enough, harder to find.  Anyone with access to a university library should be able to dig up some real gems:  <em>What's Wrong With the World</em>, <em>The Outline of Sanity</em>, <em>Robert Browning</em>, <em>St. Thomas Aquinas</em> or my favorite novel, <em>The Napoleon of Notting Hill</em>.  The last two books are currently in print.
<p>
<HR>

<H2>If you liked Chesterton you'll love...</H2>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.geocities.com/Paris/7990/">Hilaire Belloc</A>, a friend and fellow Distributivist,
<LI>the phantasies of <A HREF = "ftp://kuyper.cs.pitt.edu/ebooks/HTML/macdonald/">George MacDonald</A>,
<LI>and the novels of <A HREF = "http://www.chelmsford.com/home/daved/">Charles Williams</A>.
</UL>

<HR>

<p>
