<TITLE>SUBSCRIPTION INFO</TITLE>


</HEAD> <BODY BACKGROUND="../images/bg-b.gif"> <CENTER> <A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=top
SRC="../images/subsc.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0><IMG ALIGN=top
SRC="../images/ription.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0></A><A
HREF="premiums.html"><IMG
ALIGN=top SRC="../images/05.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0></A> <BLOCKQUOTE>
</CENTER> <TT><B><FONT SIZE=+3>Why Subscribe?</FONT></B></TT> <P>
<FONT SIZE = +2><B>Our Winter Subscription Drive raised over
$1,036,000. Thank you to all who pledged.</B></FONT> 

<P>
During the winter, we raise the funds to support both KCRW and
National Public Radio.  This is the time that we ask for the
dollars to support programs like <B>Morning Edition</B> and <B>All
Things Considered</B> as well as our own local broadcast schedule
and our website, KCRWWW.
<P>
We provide KCRWWW as a free service to an expanding worldwide
audience.  We need your help to keep it on-line and free.  Already,
in 1996, we have received praise in <I>P.C. Week</I>, we have been
featured as Real Audio's Site of the Week, and we have been awarded
the three stars by Magellan for our web-only show, <A
HREF="/hw/index.html">Hollywood Wrap</A>. 

<P>
Congress has already substantially reduced the budget for the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the agency that provides the
federal dollars to stations like KCRW.  They've reduced the
appropriation 15 percent this year, 35 percent the year after, and
right now there is no allocation at all after this coming October.

<P>
No other democracy spends so little public and listener dollars
to sustain its public broadcasting system.  Other countries spend
two to four times more per capita to support their public radio and
television services.
<P>
If you add up all the dollars from every source -- government,
corporate and foundation, as well as listener dollars -- the US comes
out at the bottom of the list.
<P>
No matter how you come down on the issue of federal grants, the
fact is that right now your voluntary contribution is more crucial
than ever to the future of KCRW.
<P>
Over the past 3 years the total operating costs for KCRW rose 30
percent while the federal appropriation declined 25 percent.  Only
KCRW's growing popularity and the willingness of listeners to
subscribe and increase their average donations, has kept us in the
black.
<P>More than 70 % of our budget comes from individual listeners like
you.  Not only do we need new subscribers, but we're depending on
those of you who have supported us in the past, to take this
opportunity to renew your subscription.
<P>
WE URGE YOU TO:
<P>...Become an <A HREF = "ap.html">Angel</A> for just a dollar a
day, and receive a KCRW celebrity black wool jacket or one of our
elegant ballistic nylon and leather business and travel bags.
<P>
...<A HREF="/cgi/s-filter.pl/b/s-form.html ">Subscribe</A> for only
$25. Increase your pledge to receive our popular matching T-shirts, sweatshirts and mugs.
<P>
<B>THESE ARE CRITICAL TIMES FOR PUBLIC BROADCASTING.  ONLY THOSE
STATIONS THAT CAN DEMONSTRATE LISTENER SUPPORT WILL SURVIVE.</B><P>
<CENTER><TT><B><FONT SIZE=+4><A HREF="/cgi/s-filter.pl/b/s-form.html
">SUBSCRIBE NOW</A></FONT></B></TT> <P> <P> <A HREF="../m.html"><IMG
ALIGN=top SRC="../images/kcrwww.gif" WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=48
BORDER=0></A> </CENTER



</BODY> </HTML>


