<HEAD>

<TITLE>RARE ON AIR I</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/bg-g.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="/images/music.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
</CENTER>
<TT><H2><B><FONT SIZE=+3>RARE ON AIR</FONT>, VOLUME ONE</B></H2></TT>
<P>
<A HREF="/images/roa1-l.jpg"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/images/roa1-s.gif"
WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=150 BORDER=0 HSPACE=20></A>
For the past 11 years, <B>KCRW</B>'s innovative music programs have
presented live on-air performances several times a week from the station's
performance studio. The variety of musicians who have performed reflect the wide
ranging styles and genres that make up <B>KCRW</B>'s eclectic music programs.
R.E.M., Tom Waits, Rickie Lee Jones, Charlie Haden, Liz Phair, The Drummers of
Burundi and PJ Harvey have all performed live in recent years.

Fortunately, all of the performances are recorded for posterity directly to two
track tape, so these on-air moments are preserved in their live and unpolished
state. The musicians all perform together in one room, and the atmosphere in the
studio is casual and loose. The spontaneity and energy contained in many of these
performances is often unmatched by heavily produced commercial recordings. 

In 1994, <B>KCRW</B> produced Rare on Air, Volume One (Mammoth Records MR0074-2)
which brought together 16 memorable takes from the <B>KCRW</B> live performance
archives. The album was produced by "Morning Becomes Eclectic" host Chris
Douridas and <B>KCRW</B> Production Director Bob Carlson
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>The line-up is as follows:</B></TT></FONT><P>
<B>
<UL>
	<LI>Prelude	Leonard Cohen - Poem 
</UL>

<OL>
	<LI>		Tori Amos - Silent All These Years
	<LI>		John Cale - Cordoba
	<LI>		Peter Himmelman - Always in Disguise
	<LI>		Evan Dando w/ Juliana Hatfield - My Drug Buddy
	<LI>		Michael Penn - Coal
	<LI>		X - Arms for Hostages
	<LI>		Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds - God's Hotel
	<LI>		Beck - Mexico
	<LI>		Los Lobos - Peace
	<LI>		Lindsey Buckingham - Never Going Back Again
	<LI>		Mark Isham - The Moderns
	<LI> 		Brendan Perry - The Captive Heart
	<LI> 		Natalie Merchant - How You've Grown
	<LI> 		Lucinda Williams - Which Will
	<LI>		David Wilcox - Chet Baker's Unsung Swan Song
</OL>
</B>


<P>
The album received four stars in Rolling Stone magazine
(July 14-28, 1994). In the review, author John McAlley called the album an 
"unlikely treasure trove," and said that it is "suffused with the kind of
searching music and hushed immediacy that defined, in the pre-MTV glory days of
rock radio, the solitary late-night FM-listening experience."
<P>
The album art was designed by Jaime Calire, who also produced <B>KCRW</B>'s
unusual animated movie trailer, called "Highwire," which plays before films shown
at Laemmle and Landmark theaters in Southern California. You can reach him via
THE FRONT (Voice: (310) 312-5702)
<P>

<B>
Rare on Air, Vol. 1 is avalable at music stores worldwide or through <A HREF="http://www.mammoth.com">Mammoth Records</A>.<P>
<A HREF="roa2.html">Rare on Air, Volume Two</A> was released by Mammoth in
August 1995.
</B>


	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
