<HEAD>

<TITLE>KCRW BOOKWORM</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/bg-c.gif">
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0></A><FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>BOOKWORM</B></TT></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>AIRS THURSDAY FROM 2 TO 2:30 PM</FONT>

<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE = +2><B>LISTEN to shows you missed.  
<P>Visit <A HREF="bwlisten.html">Bookworm's Listening Room</A>.</B></FONT><P>
<HR WIDTH=15%>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><TT><B>February 1997</B></TT></H2><P>
<H2><TT><B>February 6:</B></TT></H2>
<P>
<DL><DD><B>Michael Ondaatje</B> <I>The English Patient</I> (Viking) The Booker-Prize winner seems to be one of the very few writers who appreciates the screen adaptation of his work.  Ondaatje on editing, consciousness, character and passion.</DL>
<P>
<H2><TT><B>February 13:</B></TT></H2>
<P>
<DL><DD><B>Tobias Wolf</B> <I>The Night in Question</I> (Knopf) Tobias Wolf on the ethical questions that animate the dramatic heart of his stories.  An intense analysis of fiction's relation to truth.</DL>
<P>
<H2><TT><B>February 20:</B></TT></H2>
<P>
<DL><DD><B>Lee Smith</B> <I>The Christmas Letters</I> (Algonquin) Lee Smith actively loves her characters; her warmth towards them drives their stories.  A conversation about fiction writing as a natural activity-- with roots in childhood, family gossip and country music.</DL>
<P>
<H2><TT><B>February 27:</B></TT></H2>
<P>
<DL><DD><B>John Stepling</B> <I>Sea of Cortz and Other Plays</I> (Sun & Moon) The stage area and the wings are presented as metaphors for the conscious and the unconscious minds  in this unusual discussion of drama and theatrical space.</DL>
<P>

<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H2><TT><B>Bookworm's Library:</B></TT></H2>
<P>
<DL><DD><B>Damned to Fame: The Life of Samuel Beckett</B> by James Knowlson  (Simon & Schuster)</DL><P>

<DL><DD><B>A Mammal's Notebook</B>  by Erik Satie  (Atlas Press)</DL><P>

<DL><DD><B>Last Comes the Egg</B>  by Bruce Duffy  (Simon & Schuster)</DL><P>

<DL><DD><B>707 Scott Street: The Journal of John Wieners  </B> (Sun & Moon Press)</DL><P>

<DL><DD><B>Guided Tours of Hell: Novellas</B> by Francine Prose  (Metropolitan Books)</DL><P>


</BLOCKQUOTE>


