<TITLE>KCRW PLAYHOUSE</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/bg-c.gif"> <A HREF="index.html"><IMG
ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif" WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0><BR
clear=left><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif" WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0></A><FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>KCRW
PLAYHOUSE</B></TT></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE= -1>AIRS SUNDAY, 6 - 8 PM</FONT>  <BR CLEAR=ALL>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>



<H2><TT><B>Sunday, February 16</B></TT></H2> <P>
<P>

<UL>
      <LI><B>Dark Star</B> A dramatic reconstruction of the last years of Wilfred Owen, poet and soldier of the First World War.  Owen's poetry evokes the emotional and physical experience of those who fought and lost their lives, or themselves.  (BBC)
</UL> 

<P>
<H2><TT><B>Sunday, February 23</B></TT></H2>

<UL>
      <LI><B>Light Up The Sky</B> The Goodman Theatre's production of this classic 1948 Moss Hart comedy is a fast-paced, hilarious, and ultimately loving look inside show business, set just before and immediately after a Broadway-bound play meets its first audience.  (Chicago Theatres On the Air)
	<LI><B>Contemporary Korean Short Stories: "The Rock"</B> by Tong-ni Kim, portrays people who have not found a niche in Korea's highly structured society.  Read by Freda Foh Shen from a translation by Chong-Wha Chung, published in <I>Modern Korean Literature</I> by Kegan Paul International.  And, "Seoul, 1964 Winter", by Sung-0k Kim, a slangy, sardonic reading by Sung Kyu Park (Steve Park), Ro-Soo Park (Tim Lounibos) and Jungha Suk (Eric Steinberg); from a translation by Marshall R. Phil, published in I>Land of Exile</I> by M.E. Sharpe.  (KCRW/Society of Heritage Performers production)  
</UL> 


