<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W30//DTD W3 HTML 2.0//EN"><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>THE POLITICS OF CULTURE</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../images/bg-c.gif"><A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0 HSPACE=0><BR clear=left><A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0 HSPACE = 0></A><FONT SIZE=+4><TT><B>POLITICS OF CULTURE</B></TT></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE = +1> VARIOUS HOSTS </FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=-1>AIRS TUESDAY FROM 2 TO 2:30 PM<BR CLEAR=left></FONT><P><BLOCKQUOTE><ul><li>Sometimes a panel discussion about current controversies in the cultural world, other times and in-depth interview with an author or leading figures in media, the arts, entertainment or politics, <i>The Politics of Culture</i> examines the intersection where the world of politics and culture meet and sometimes collide. <BR CLEAR = LEFT><br><CENTER><TABLE WIDTH = 500 BORDER = 1 CELLPADDING = 3><TR><TH><TT>Date</TT></TH><TH><TT>Guest/Topic</TT></TH><TH><TT>Listen</TT></TH></TR>

<TR><TD><TT>2/04/97</TT></TD><TD><TT>Mickey Kaus interviews <B>Ann Louise Bardach</B> about the Swiss during WWII, and thier handling of Jewish assets during the holocaust.   Ann Louise Bardach wrote an  article on this subject that will appear in the upcoming issue of <I>Vanity Fari</I>. </TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc70204.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>

<TR><TD><TT>1/28/97</TT></TD><TD><TT>It caused a stir in New York, received raves and pans, and now it's here, at the UCLA/Armand Hammer Museum in Westwood.  Join us for a conversation about the controversial exhibit "Too Jewish? Challenging Traditional Identities," Tuesday at 2. Hosted by <B>Marlene Adler Marks</B> of the Jewish Journal.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc70128.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>

<TR><TD><TT>1/21/97</TT></TD><TD><TT><B>Edward Goldman</B> hosts a warm, friendly conversation with <B>John Richardson</B>, author of the definitive biography of Picasso.  Volume 1 met with great critical and popular acclaim, and now Mr. Richardson, who was a close personal friend of the artist, discusses Volume 2, "A Life of Picasso," which covers the ten most prolific and dramatic years of Picasso's life.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc70121.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>


<TR><TD><TT>1/14/97</TT></TD><TD><TT>Was she a fascist, a socialist or just an actress in the greatest role of her life?  "Time" Magazine film critic <B>Richard Schickel</B> hosts a discussion of "Evita" - and asks whether Hollywood has gone too far in making a pop icon out of the legendary Argentinian first lady.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc70114.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>


<TR><TD><TT>1/7/97</TT></TD><TD><TT>She turned down a grant from the N.E.A. on principle -- now she's about to receive its highest honor.  After many decades as a pioneering modern dance artist, the woman called the conscience of dance is closing up shop.  Join L.A. Chamber Ballet Director Raiford Rogers for an in-depth interview with <B>Bella Lewitzky</B></TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc70107.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>

<!--TR--><TD><TT>12/30/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>Race, politics and California are in the spotlight as Warren Olney interviews Dale Maharidge, author of the new book, "The Coming White Minority."</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61230.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR>



<TR><TD><TT>12/03/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>Chaim Herzog talks about his new book <I>Living History</I>, a memoir.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61203.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD><TT>11/26/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>MOCA's new exhibit Walt Disney's Concert Hall: a Celebration of Music and Architecture pays homage to an as of yet unbuilt landmark.  Join Edward goldman for a conversation with Nicolai Ourosoff, Architecture critic of the Los Angeles Times and Richard Koshalek, Director of the Museum of Contemporary Art.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61126.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD><TT>11/19/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>The Marc Chagall Exhibit at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art was quickly assembled in a classic demonstration of curatorial skill.  Join Edward goldman for a conversation with the curators who pulled off this minor miracle.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61119.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD><TT>11/12/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>Edward Goldman talks to Sasha Anawald, author of the book <I>The Joffrey: Robert Joffrey and the Making of an American Dance Company</I>.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61112.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD><TT>11/05/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>Matt Miller and Robert Scheer talk to Judge Robert Bork about his new book, <I>Slouching Toward Gemorrah: Modern Liberalism and American Decline</I>.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61105.ram"><IMG SRC = "../images/ra.gif" WIDTH = 25 HEIGHT = 36 BORDER = 0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD><TT>10/22/96</TT></TD><TD><TT>Harry Shearer talks to author and attorney Jeffery Toobin about his book <I>The Run of his Life: People vs. OJ</I>.</TT></TD><TH><A HREF = "http://www.kcrw.org/ra/pc61022.ram"><IMG SRC = "