<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W30//DTD W3 HTML 2.0//EN"><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>KCRW THOUGHTS ON THEATRE</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../images/bg-c.gif"><A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0 HSPACE=0><BR clear=left><A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0 HSPACE = 0></A><FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>THOUGHTS ON THEATRE</B></TT></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=-1>AIRS THURSDAYS AT 6:55<BR CLEAR=left></FONT><P><BLOCKQUOTE>Thoughts on Theatre is hosted by Robert Windeler.<BR><BR><BR><A HREF="#PastShows">Past Shows</A><BR><A HREF="ttbio.htm">Robert Windeler's Biography.</A><BR><BR><B>January 30, 1997</B><BR><BR>	<P>KCRW/National Public Radio Broadcast, January 30, 1997 <BR><P><P>This is Robert Windeler, with Thoughts on Theatre.

KCRW/National Public Radio Broadcast, January 30, 1997 

This is Robert Windeler, with Thoughts on Theatre.
If you're a serious Wagnerian, or simply someone who likes to take in the complete opera canon at its best, I would urge to try to get to the stunning Los Angeles Opera production of "Tristan und Isolde" that opened last night at the Music Center.  I say "try," because Saturday's matinee performance is sold out, and the remaining five evening performances are already close to capacity.  This "Tristan and Isolde" is both a hit, and an event with a capital E.  Chief among its many virtues is the debut performance of Renate Behle, an Austrian soprano.  She is singing the role of Isolde for the first time, and magnificently.  Behle is also making her Los Angeles Opera debut.  Siegfied Jerusalem, a heldentenor in the other title role, is almost her equal vocally, but his acting is a bit leaden, which tends to throw the whole opera Behle's way.  Jerusalem is just not believeable as a creature of turnabout passion, "filial" devotion and soldierly duty.  He sings very well to the audience, but not to his fellow actors or to the opera itself.  We sense no torment in his Tristan's soul.  (Jerusalem also perspires profusely, and distractingly, under the weight of his black velvet costume.)  Jorma Hynninen, the Finnish baritone, supplies solid support as Tristan's groom, and mezzo-soprano Jane Henschell, as Isolde's maid, does even better than that.  And bass-baritone Donald McIntyre is just fine in the only other major singing role, the pre-cuckolded King of Cornwall.  In this watershed Wagner opera, the orchestra must be in top form, and this one is, under conductor Richard Armstrong.   Hearing them play the overture, with its introduction of atonalities, and the leitmotifs throughout the opera, is to understand why Wagner's glorious "Tristan" score is so groundbreaking in its instrumental passages.  But the real co-star of this production is David Hockney, who has done more than design the vivid sets and costumes or merely update those for his 1987 production of "Tristan and Isolde" at the Los Angeles Opera.  Hockney "conceived and directed" this mounting, according to the program, with help from Stephen Pickover on the actual staging.  Hockney's original take is sometimes over the top: the second-act tree branches look like large intestines; the increasingly raked stage (15, 30 and 45 degrees as the three acts progress) makes no real artistic plot and is awkward for the actors to negotiate.  And Isolde and her maid's birght red and green velvet dresses in the first act are straight out a a Victorian Christmas.  But his vision seems honestly responsive to his hearing of Wagner's music, and not dependent on anyone's tradition.  A few caveats: the knife-fight choreography is embarrassingly unbelieveable.  The slimmish plot line (however endlessly analyzed and interpreted) often seems not to justify the opera's five-hour length--and hence 6:30 starting time.  (Although I must say, the production as a whole is so good it doesn't seem like five hours until you hit the parking lot.)  To non-Wagnerians that third act drags a bit both dramatically and musically, at least until Isolde reappears and sings her final aria, the Liebestod.  (And, indeed, many people went home last night after the second intermission.)  But this "Tristan" is still extremely special, and worth your major effort.
 Gogi Grant, at the Hollywood Roosevelt Cinegrill through Saturday night, is also a worthwhile event, for lovers of the popular music from the 1950s and before.  Yes, Grant finally sings her hit, "The Wayward Wind," but almost in passing, near the end of her generous set.  The stylish focus of her act is the lyrics of Dorothy Fields.  Grant is in fine voice and her return to performing is long overdue.  She seemed under-rehearsed on opening night, however, and blew way too many lyrics.  Shelly Markham heads a terrific backup quartet.

This is Robert Windeler, with Thoughts on Theatre.





