<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>KCRW- AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT  SRC="../images/09.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0 HSPACE=40 VSPACE=10>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+4><TT><B>AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL</B></TT></FONT>
<BR>
<B>GENERAL INFO</B>
<P>
Every month, in conjunction with <A HREF="http://www.amnesty.org"><B>Amnesty International</B></A>, <B><A HREF="/m.html">KCRW</A></B> invites its listeners to participate in an URGENT ACTION on behalf of a prisoner of conscience. We suggest that you pass this material on to others who may also be interested in participating in this letter-writing program.
<P>
Amnesty International is an independent worldwide movement working for the international protection of human rights.  It seeks the release of men and women detained anywhere because of their beliefs, color, sex, ethnic origin, language or religious creed, provided they have not used nor advocated violence.  These are termed prisoners of conscience.  It works for fair and prompt trials for all political prisoners and works on behalf of such people detained without charge or trial.  It opposes the death penalty, torture or other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment of all prisoners without reservation.
<P>
&nbsp;
<P>
<B>PRISONER OF CONSCIENCE:</B>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><TT><B>Godwin Agbroko</B></TT></FONT><P>

<DD><B>JANUARY 1997<BR> <DD>COUNTRY: Nigeria</B>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>
Godwin Agbroko (aged about 40) is a Nigerian journalist who was arrested a month ago in his Lagos office.  As an editor of "The Week" news magazine, he was probably arrested in connection with a recent article exposing divisions within senior military officers.  No official reason, however, has been given for his detention.
 
Godwin Agbroko was arrested by the Lagos security police and later on transferred to the capital city of Abuja where he is held without charge or trial.  The State Security Decree under which he is being detained provides for the indefinite detention of any person deemed to be a threat to the security or the economy of the state.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><TT><B>BACKGROUND INFORMATION:</B></TT></FONT><BR>
Senior journalists on "The Week" have previously been detained without charge or trial, including Godwin Agbroko, on at least two other occasions.  The above decree has been used extensively to detain journalists and other government critics, sometimes for months or years.  Detainees have been held in harsh and life-threatening conditions.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><TT><B>RECOMMENDED ACTION:</B></TT></FONT><BR>
<UL><LI>Please send telegrams/telexes/express/airmail letters to (Airmail postage: 60 cents):
<DD>General Sani Abacha
<DD>Chairman, Provisional Ruling Council
<DD>State House
<DD>ABUJA, Federal Capital Territory
<DD>NIGERIA
<DD>[Telegrams:  General Abacha, Abuja, Nigeria]
<DD>Fax: 011-234-9-523-2138

<P> In your letter
<P>
<UL>
<LI>- express concern at the arrest and continued detention without charge or trial of Godwin Agbroko. Amnesty International considers him to be a prisoner of conscience.

<LI>- urge that he be given immediate access to his family and to a doctor and lawyer of his choice.

<LI>- appeal for his immediate and unconditional release if he is not to be charged with a recognizable criminal offense.

</UL>

<P>
<B>Please be courteous and send your letter promptly.</B>
</UL>
<P>
Remember that Amnesty International opposes human rights violations wherever they occur,but not governments or political systems.  LETTERS SHOULD NOT BE ACCUSATORY. It is better to assume that the authorities are, in fact, willing to seek a remedy for violations of human rights if they are properly informed.
<P>
