which includes a one-year subscription to KCRW, and $80 for each
additional set. <A HREF="/cgi/s-filter.pl/b/s-form.html"><FONT SIZE = +2>Order
now.</FONT></A></B></TT>

<P>
<HR WIDTH = 20%>
<P>

<CENTER><H2><TT>ABOUT THE DIRECTOR AND PRODUCERS</TT></H2></CENTER>



<DL>



<DT><B>DIRECTOR</B>



<P>

<DD><B>Joan Micklin Silver</B> writes and directs film, television and theater. 

She is a vice

president of Silverfilm Productions, Inc.



<DD>Her films include Hester Street (1975), which earned her a Writers Guild

nomination for

best screenplay and Carol Kane an Academy Award nomination as Best Actress;

Between The

Lines (1976); Chilly Scenes of Winter (originally released as Head Over Heels

(1976) but

retitled and re-released in 1981); Crossing Delancey (1988), starring Amy Irving

and

Peter Riegert; Loverboy (1989); and Big Girls Don't Cry (1991).



<DD>For theater she has directed many plays and musicals including "Album"

(1980), "Maybe I'm

Doing It Wrong" (1981), and "A...My Name is Alice" (1984), co-conceived with

Julianne

Boyd, which ran for a year off-Broadway and has played across the country.  A new

production, "A...My Name is Still Alice" opened in 1992.



<DD>Her television films include "Bernice Bobs Her Hair" (PBS, 1975) starring

Shelley Duvall

and based on a story by F. Scott Fitzgerald; "Finnegan Begin Again" (1984) with

Robert

Preston and Mary Tyler Moore for HBO; "Parole Board" (Prison Stories: Women on

the Inside

(1990) for HBO); and "A Private Matter" (1992) for HBO starring Sissy Spacek and

Aidan

Quinn.

<P>







<DT><B>PRODUCERS</B>

<P>



<DD><B>Lori McGlinchey</B> is Program Director of the National Yiddish Book

Center.  A graduate of

Amherst College and the Uriel Weinreich Yiddish Program at Columbia University,

she is

currently pursuing graduate study in Yiddish literature at Harvard University. 

Ms.

McGlinchey is a writer and editor for Der Pakn-treger, the magazine of the

National

Yiddish Book Center.

<P>

<DD><B>Johanna Cooper</B> is an award-winning radio and video producer living in

Los Angeles.  She

is a graduate of the USC School of Cinema-Television and currently coordinates

Los

Angeles-area activities for the National Yiddish Book Center.

<P>

<DD><B>Roz Abraham</B> is the producer of the award-winning radio series "Short

Stories from Modern

Mexico."  She is a consultant in fine arts programming and holds a masters in art

history

from the University of Mexico.  Yiddish is her native language.



<P>

<DT><B>EXECUTIVE PRODUCERS</B>



<P>

<DD><B>Aaron Lansky</B> is founder and president of the National Yiddish Book

Center, a nonprofit

organization for the preservation and revitalization of Yiddish culture.  Over

the years

this group has won international recognition for its dramatic campaign to rescue

unwanted

and discarded Yiddish books and return them to active use.  Mr. Lansky and his

co-workers

have saved more than one million volumes, often racing through the night to

rescue books

from basements, attics, garbage dumpsters and demolition sites.  The ongoing

educational

and cultural work of the National Yiddish Book Center has fired the imagination

of

thousands.  The Center is now the fastest growing Jewish cultural organization in

America.



<DD>A native of New Bedford, Massachusetts, Aaron Lansky holds a B.A. in Modern

Jewish

History from Hampshire College, an M.A. in East European Jewish Studies from

McGill

University and is a graduate of the Uriel Weinreich Yiddish Program at Columbia

University.  A popular lecturer throughout the United States, Canada and Israel,

he has

taught courses in Yiddish literature at Hampshire College, The University of

Massachusetts, and the Yiddish Book Center's many educational programs for

college

students and adults.



<DD>Mr. Lansky has received numerous awards and recognitions for his practical

work on behalf

of Yiddish culture.  He was named a MacArthur Fellow in 1989.



<P>

<DD><B>Ruth Seymour</B> is the General Manager of <B>KCRW</B>, the National

Public Radio flagship station

for Southern California.



<DD>She has worked in public radio since 1961, and she has been with <B>KCRW</B>

since 1978.  Under

her leadership, the station's audience has grown from several thousand listeners

to more

than 450,000.  The station's budget has grown from a mere $100,000 in 1978 to

over $4.7

million in 1993.



<DD><B>KCRW</B> has evolved an important and dynamic news format, which allows it

to present ongoing

news and analysis and enables it to respond to major crisis in the community or

the

world.  Ms. Seymour created the station's daily one-hour program, "Which Way,

L.A.?,"

anchored by Warren Olney, in response to the L.A riots of April 1992.  She serves

as its

executive producer.  The New York Times hailed the program as "the main broadcast

forum

for serious issues in the troubled Los Angeles area." In addition to pioneering

innovative news and public affairs, <B>KCRW</B> produces and broadcasts more

radio drama than

any other station in the U.S.



<DD>Throughout her career, Ms. Seymour has developed programs that have won most

of radio's

top awards.  Apart from her administrative responsibilities at <B>KCRW</B>, Ruth

Seymour is

perhaps best known to the station's listeners as an on-air programmer and

interviewer. 

She herself anchored the station's coverage of the Gulf War, the Soviet Coup and

the L.A.

riots.  She hosts a weekly half-hour program on international and national

affairs.  Her

three-hour annual Chanukah program receives more mail than any single program the

station

broadcasts.



