<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>KCRW BOOKWORM</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/bg-c.gif">
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96 BORDER=0></A>
<FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>BOOKWORM'S LISTENING ROOM</B></TT></FONT>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>HOSTED BY MICHAEL SILVERBLATT<BR>BOOKWORM AIRS THURSDAYS FROM 2 - 2:30 PM</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE = +1>WHO'S ON <A HREF="bookworm.html"></FONT><FONT SIZE = +2>BOOKWORM</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE = +1>THIS MONTH?</FONT>
</CENTER>

<P>
<!-BEGINNING OF BOOKWORM PROGRAM ENTRTY->

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw70206.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Michael Ondaatje</B><I>The English Patient </I> (Viking)he Booker-Prize winner seems to be one of the very few writers who appreciates the screen adaptation of his work. Ondaatje on editing, consciousness, character and passion..  Aired Thursday, February 6, 1997.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw70130.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Michael Lally</B><I> Can't Be Wrong</I> (Coffee House Press) Michael Lally--part Frank Sinatra, part William Saroyan--is an auditory seducer. This poet will leave you panting.  Aired Thursday, January 30, 1997.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw70123.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Robert Olen Butler</B> <I>Tabloid Dreams</I> (Holt) The characters from supermarket tabloids reveal their inner  truths in Pulitzer Prize-winner Butler's poetic stories..  Aired Thursday, January 23, 1997.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw70116.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Elena Poniatowska</B> <I>Tinisima</I> (Farrar, Straus & Giroux) Mexico's "premiere woman of letters" on Tina Modotti--photographer, model, revolutionary--the subject of this biographical novel.  Aired Thursday, January 16, 1997.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw70109.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Paul Theroux</B> <I>My Other Life</I> (Houghton Mifflin) This autobiography is a supernatural story in disguise--hear Paul Theroux's Dr. Jeckyll explain the demonic nature of Paul Theroux's Mr. Hyde.  Aired Thursday, January 8, 1997.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61226.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Brad Gooch</B> <I>The Golden Age of Promiscuity</I> (Knopf) Brad Gooch reveals the structure of the heroic quest that underlies this misunderstood and frequently reviled novel.  Aired Thursday, December 26, 1996.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61219.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Junot Diaz</B> <I>Drown</I> (Riverhead) Diaz' stories render the young-immigrant experience in harsh, unforgettable rhythms.  Here Diaz discusses the art of telling the truth.   Aired Thursday, December 19, 1996.</DL><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61212.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Sigrid Nunez</B> <I>Naked Sleeper</I>  (Harper Collins) A discussion about the oldest of sob stories: the sub-genre known as the "womans weepie."  Sigrid Nunez on gender and narrative strategy.  Aired Thursday, December 12, 1996.</DL><BR><A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61205.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Frank McCourt</B> <I>Angela's Ashes</I> (Scribner)  Memories have becomes trendy, but Frank McCourt's emotional masterpiece bucks the trend.  A conversation about how this powerful work -- comprised of comedy and pain, told in the beautifully sustained tones of an Irish tenor -- finally came to be.  Aired Thursday, December 5, 1996.</DL><BR><A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61121.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Joan Didion</B> <I>The Last Thing He Wanted</I> (Knopf) Part Two.  Aired Thursday, November 21, 1996.</DL>
<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61114.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Joan Didion</B> <I>The Last Thing He Wanted</I> (Knopf) Part one of a special two-part interview with a novelist whose works have defined the essences of American places (Los Angeles, Miami, New York) and times (the sixties, the seventies, the eighties).  Topics include the influences of T.S. Eliot, Joseph Conrad, Ernest Hemingway, and her contemporary, Joyce Carol Oates, the nature of resonance and the role of accident and intuition in the writing of novels. Aired Thursday, November 14, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61107.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Ellen Brodkey</B> <I>This Wild Darkness: The Story of My Death</I> by <B>Harold Brodkey</B> (Metropolitan Books) Ellen Brodkey, widow and editor, joins Bookworm in a memorial to the life and death of American writer Harold Brodkey on the occasion of the publication of his AIDS journal. Aired Thursday, November 7, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61031.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>E. Annie Proulx</B> <I>Accordion Crimes</I> (Scribner) In her newest book, the Pulitzer Prize-winning novelistpresents an historical cavalcade: her vision of the violence that has been perpetuated against emergingminority cultures. Aired Thursday, October 31, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61024.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Thom Jones</B> <I>Cold Snap</I> (Little Brown) More than a decade passed between the author's stint at the Iowa Writers' Workshop and the publication of his first book. How does a writer endure the hard times?.  Aired Thursday, October 24, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61017.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Lucille Clifton</B> <I>The Terrible Stories</I> (BOA Editions) Her influences, inclinaiton toward short poems and decision to tell "the terrible stories" are discussed by the poet.  Aired Thursday, October 17, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61010.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><I>From Idea to Publication: Nature Writing Today</I> A panel discussion with author <B>Terry Tempest  Williams</B>, <I>Refuge</I> (Ecco); <I>Orion Magazine</I> editor <B>George Russell</B>; and literary agent <B>Elizabeth Grossman</B>.  Aired Thursday, October 10, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw61003.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL> <I>Going Back to Bisbee </I><B>Richard Shelton  </B> (University of Arizona Press) The winner of the Western States Book Award for creative non-fiction discusses his memoir of the desert of the American Southwest. Aired Thursday, October 3, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60919.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL> <I>Nature and Childhood </I><B>Robert Michael Pyle  </B> <I>The Thunder Tree </I> (Houghton Mifflin) and <B>Scott Russell Sanders  </B> <I>Writing from the Center </I>(Indiana University Press) The writers discuss how adult mentors affect a child's attitude toward the natural world and how writing penetrates one's inner wilderness--the wilderness of imagination. Aired Thursday, September,19 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60912.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><I>What is Nature Literacty? </I><B>Robert Hass </B><I>Sun Under Wood </I> (Ecco)<B>David Abram </B><I>The Spell of the Senuous</I> (Pantheon)<B>Alison Hawthorne Deming </B><I>Science and Other Poems</I> (Louisiana State University Press)  Has literacy alienated us from nature? If written language is the cause of separation, can nature-writing provide a way to re-connect? The panelists strive to answer those questions, exploring early oral cultures and the development of the written alphabet. Aired Thursday, September, 12 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60905.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Barry Lopez </B><I>Field Notes </I> (Avon) Can nature-writing heal the rift between civilzation and nature?  Does activism disturb the making of art? National Book Award winner Lopez discusses the cultural tradition of nature writing. Aired Thursday, September, 5 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60829.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Reynolds Price  </B> <I>Three Gospels </I> (Scribners)On the harshness of faith and the rigors of translation: To most people, the Gospels have the mellifluous sound of the King James version. Novelist Reynolds Price translates two of the Gospels from the original Greek, and the results are startling.Aired Thursday, August 29, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60822.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Judith Freeman </B><I>A Desert of Pure Feeling </I> (Knopf)  and<B>Jane Mendelsohn </B><I>I Was Amelia Earhart</I> (Knopf)A  metaphor for a womans spiritual journey--an ocean voyage by cruiser, in the first, and a dangerous airplane flight, in the second--is at the core of each of these eerie, new novels.Aired Thursday, August 22, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60808.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Richard Ford </B> <I>Independence Day </I> (Vintage)A summit conference on Fords Pulitzer Prize-winning novel establishes once and for all that the book, said to be full of arrogance and irony, is about compromise and sincerity.Aired Thursday, August 8, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60801.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Robert Bly </B><I>The Sibling Society </I> (Addison Wesley)The relationship between interpretation and story-telling stands, in this conversation,for the relationships between meaning and action, old and young,  responsibility and shallowness.Aired Thursday, August 1, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60718.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Grace Paley</B> <I>The Collected Stories</I> (Farrar, Straus & Giroux)   The invaluable, funny, mischief-makerGrace Paley speaks of Jews, men, politics, children and the voices that have entered her permanent, memorable stories.Aired Thursday, July 18, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60711.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Barbara Guest</B> <I>Selected Poems; Fair Realism</I> (Sun & Moon)   "What is Truth?" is the central questionof Modern Poetry. Barbara Guest approaches that question delicately, wittily and unpretentiously.Aired Thursday, July 11, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60627.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>David Shields</B> <I>Remote</I> (Knopf) Aired Thursday, June 27, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60620.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Nicholson Baker</B> <I>The Size of Thoughts</I> (Random House) Aired Thursday, June 20, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60613.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Duff Brenna</B> <I>The Holy Book of the Beard</I> (Doubleday) <BR><B>Jennifer Egan</B> <I>Emerald City and Other Shories</I> (Doubleday) Aired Thursday, June 13, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60606.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Jane Smiley</B> <I>Moo</I> (Ballantine) Aired Thursday, June 6, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60530.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Hans Magnus Enzenberger</B> <I>Civil Wars</I> (The New Press) The eminent German poet and culture critic explores the future of literacy and literary culture. A spiky new Asian-American voice tells de-centered tales of Honolulu pop culture.Aired Thursday, May 30, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60523.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Zamora Zinmark</B> <I>Rolling the R's</I> (Kaya Production) A spiky new Asian-American voice tells de-centered tales of Honolulu pop culture.Aired Thursday, May 23, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60516.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Yellow Bay Writer's Workshop</B>  Bill Kitteredge and Annick Smicth, the founding directors of the Yellow Bay Writer's Workshop in Montana, tell about what goes on at one of the most spirited summer writing workshops in America.Aired Thursday, May 16, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw60502.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Mark Doty</B> <I>Heaven's Coast, Atlantis</I> (Harper Collins) Poet Mark Doty's memoir is an expression of grief over his lover's death.  How do prose and poetry compare as vehicles for emotion?  Aired Thursday, May 2, 1996.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw51218.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Kaye Gibbons</B> <I> Sights Unseen</I> (Putnam) A child searches for its mother in three of Kaye Gibbon's novels.  What is the significance of these quests?  Aired Monday, December 18, 1995. </DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>

<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw51120.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Jay Gummerman</B> <I>Chez Chance</I> (Pantheon) Gummerman speaks about the lives of the disenfranchised dreamers in this, his first novel.  Aired Monday, December 11, 1995.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw51225.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Rick Moody</B> <I>The Ring of Brightest Angels Around Heaven</I> (Little Brown) A conversation about the literary values of Generation X.  Aired Monday, December 25, 1995.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
<A HREF="http://www.kcrw.org/ra/bw51228.ram"><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/ra.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=36></A><DL><B>Theodore Roszak</B> <I>The Memoirs of Elizabeth Frankenstein</I> The politics of gender.  When Theodore Roszak re-writes Mary Shelly, is he committing an act of gender aggression?  Aired Thursday, December 28, 1995.</DL><BR CLEAR = LEFT>
