<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>KCRW BOOKWORM</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/bg-c.gif"><A HREF="index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/12.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../images/11.gif"  WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=96
BORDER=0></A><FONT SIZE=+3><TT><B>SALMAN RUSHDIE</B></TT></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>KCRWWW SPECIAL PROGRAMMING</FONT><BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE = +2>Salman Rushdie on <I>Bookworm</I></FONT>
<BR>Part Two of Two<P><FONT SIZE = -1>[ <A HREF = "rushdie.html">Back to Listen</A> ] [ <A HREF="srtransp1.html">Part One</A> ] </A></FONT></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<TT>
<B>MS:</B> I'm speaking to Salman Rushdie, the author, of course, of <I>Midnight's Children</I>, <I>The Satanic Verses</I> and most recently, <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>.  It also seemed to me that, at least what Humpty Dumpty does when he falls is that he shatters and that the condition of shattering, being part of a sundered hole is also a primary image in these novels.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Yeah, the idea of being not just an egg but a mirror or any kind of entity that breaks and can't be put be back together is an idea that's important in the modern age because we live in fragmented and fractured societies and we don't have all the pieces.  I think the way in which we experience the world is that we don't have all the pieces that explain it. We have some of them, our knowledge and our experience and the accidents of our lives give us, if we're lucky, enough pieces with which to make enough sense of the world. But I think that all of us are conscious of the fact that there's bits missing in the picture. There are pieces of the jigsaw that aren't there. There are bits of the broken mirror that got lost. And so I think I've tired to suggest in my books that that kind of fragmented vision is actually a truthful way of writing about the world -- the world seen in fragments. In <I>Midnight's Children</I> a man sees a woman in fragments. He's a doctor and examines her because she's a veiled Muslim woman so when she's ill he can only examine her through a hole in the sheet. Over the course of many years he sees different six inch circles of her body and has to glue them together in his imagination. And having glued together in his mind these different pieces of a fractured woman he falls in love with them and ends up marrying her. I suppose that was, I hope it's a funny idea, but it's also a metaphor for the way I was trying to write. Which is to say that we do see the world in fragments and we try to make a picture of it by adding those fragments together.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> What's marvelous to me in your work is that most of the profoundest metaphors are also the funniest.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Comedy is the way it comes out with me. I don't, as it were, sit there and think now I shall be funny. I think I just have a weird head.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> But it also has the, unlike Joyce, there's a lovely improvised feel about these books. In Joyce, Joyce dreamed of a book in which you might look at any page and know exactly that that was that page in exactly that place, in exactly that novel -- all very fixed. One of his metaphors of course, is a mobilization in paralysis but it's something that afflicts, in a sense, the prose too. Here, suddenly, even under the direst circumstances it suddenly strikes the Salman Rushdie mind to do an impersonation of a young, fawning, information-heavy business executive foster brother and so suddenly, out of the blue, the peacock's tail fanning, you get two or three pages of Indian Reganese, I guess I'd call it.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> I suppose I like what I suppose in rock music would be called riffs. I think every so often these books just do go off on a riff. I mean, if it's funny my view is go with it. The great advice of Roger Rabbit is, only if it's funny, that's the only reason for doing something. I hope in that case, the case of the arrival in the middle of <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>, of the character of a kind of mad, crazed and corrupt young Indian yuppie, is partly because I wanted to say that those are, that is a generation that is inheriting the earth in India. These people who have satellite dishes instead of ears.  

<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I wanted to bring up cartoons, as a matter of fact, because they seem to have a double purpose in some way in your work. On the one hand, in <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>, for instance, there's a delightful nursery that's been made. It's walls filled by an artist friend of Aurora's with images from cartoons. In fact, at night, he creeps in and repaints the walls so the children see new adventures when they wake up. But there's also a sense of an artist being a mere caricaturist. This is the kind of art that sometimes you've been accused of and which in this book, I sense, you repudiate. The people who do merely cartoons, merely satiric commentary art, seem to be doing a far inferior thing to the thing Aurora does which is vast and mosaic and...
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> I think you've hit on something very important to me in this book which is that at one level it tries to discuss the relative value and function and nature of caricature on one hand and art on the other.  Of course, the value of that mouse, that duck and that bunny is that we all know them and therefore they become ways of talking about ourselves.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> Do you remember the famous Nabakov sentence. In an interview he leans across to Alfred Apel, the interviewer and his friend, and says, tell me, is the bunny Disney's?
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> But the bunny as we know is not Disney's. It seems to me there's a sense in which these figures, Tweety Pie and Sylvester and Tom & Jerry, these give us modern myths which are international, which require no language which therefore communicate globally. They give us a way of talking about ourselves not unlike the way in which once upon a time, the people would have used the Greek or Roman myths to talk about themselves. And so there is that reason for using them. It's easy, if one wants to talk about split personalities and dopplegangers, you start losing your audience. But if you want to talk about Superman and Clark Kent, or Batman and Bruce Wayne, everybody gets the point. So it becomes a way of talking about serious things. But also in this novel, there's the notion of caricature as oversimplification. And as something not finally worthy of serious consideration because after all the mouse, the duck and the bunny do not really have emotional complexity or depth. They have a certain limited range of possibilities. And in the same way the political caricaturist in the novel, Raman Fielding, is clearly also a person whose vision is two-dimensional, caricatured, extreme, exaggerated.  And so it's not surprising that he grows up or develops into a fairly unlikeable bullying politician whose view of the world is very simplistic and two-dimensional. The character you mentioned who paints the nursery, a bad painter called Vasco Miranda, when he becomes famous as a painter is also painting what Aurora the great artist contemptuously calls Airport Art, that's to say art which is pleasing to rich patrons but actually has no real depth, no real bite which could also be called in a way, flat or two-dimensional. Whereas Aurora, well I tried to make Aurora in a way that the reader might accept that she was a genius. One of the things I wanted to do in the novel is to contrast the genius of the true artist with the limitations of the cartoonist. And obviously I come out on the side of art.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> It seemed to be in a way to be necessary to do so because, again in the flat and one-dimensional picture that most people have of Salman Rushdie, he is someone who has been a satirist, an extreme satirist, a Lenny Bruce satirist, a gifted satirist, but the other realms of art, the spectrum of possibility of art, seems to be what's stressed in this book. And not only that, the question of something entirely missing from most cartoons, the possibility of fulfilled love. Love is something that you don't, by and large, encounter in satire, except by its absence, in cartoons, except by it frustrations -- the number of cats that never will meet their enamorata or instead are satisfied with a brick. But it does seem that the book here, <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>, is looking for, if art is a matter of life and death, what is a matter of life and death, what is important enough to be a matter of life and death?
<P><P>
<B>SR:</B> Yeah. I think you're quite right. The answer to that question is love, in this book. What persists in us is love. I think, for me, one of the great satisfactions of writing this book was that it was a novel that probably for the first time for me, actually made love the central subject of the novel. I would describe it not as a love story but as a story about love, all sorts of love. Sexual love, romantic love, mother love, the love of children for their parents, the love of God, the love of money, the love of nation and how these things work upon us and when they work when they do us good, and when they don't work how they do us ill.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> Also the things that substitute for love...
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Hatred.<P><P>
<B>MS:</B> Business.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Money in the bank.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> It seems as if the book is full of rivals for love.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Yes, I think that's right. In the central love affair in the novel which is the love affair of the narrator's parents, Aurora and Abraham, well Abraham's rival for Aurora's love is her art. And she makes it very clear to him, straight off, that there's this area of her life where she can perfectly all right by herself, thank you very much, and where he will not go. Her studio and her imagination. This in the end, I imagine, is what begins to destroy their relationship as he feels more and more cut off from her. He retreats into the world that becomes her rival for his love which is, as you said, the world of business, of money. But not just money but crime, corruption, evil. So her rival is evil I'm afraid.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I found a little book, pamphlet sized, distributed in America by a university press, it's from the British Film Institute originally. It's a book on the <I>Wizard of Oz</I>, the film that Salman Rushdie wrote and children's books and films both, seem very central, like a germination point from which the Rushdie universe unfolds.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> I've heard stories where we start, you know, we start hearing stories when we're very, very little.  And we hear them increasingly, we hear them in the movies as well as in book form. And I suppose the stories we start with, like the <I>Wizard of Oz</I>, like Alice in Wonderland, like the <I>Arabian Nights</I> stories I heard when I was a kid, shaped me very profoundly. I went on and on writing variations of them. So I guess it's all Dorothy's fault.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I feel too, that if a book doesn't have magic in it, it's not that I won't read it or appreciate it, but magic seemed the first thing.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Well I think it is the thing that we learn as children, that, to put it simply, stories are not true. That's to say, we don't go to stories to learn about ordinary, everyday truths. We go there to learn about flying horses or slippers that take you home or mirrors that you climb through, etc. The truth that these stories bring us is some deeper truth, some dream truth, some truth that we know in blood but that's not the truth of the kitchen sink.  
<P><P>
<B>MS:</B> What happens after that, after the initial love of magic, seems to me that there are two divergences. Some people, loving magic, discover art. And some people loving magic discover religion. And it seems to me that the similarities and the differences between religion and art are very much at the heart of these books and in a sense at the heart of the problem that you face in an ongoing current events, fatwa sense. That the prerogatives and needs of art are not the same as those of religion although they share an interest in the magicking of the world.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Yes, well how could they not since it does seem, if we project backwards, as though art emerged as a by product of religion. If we look at the earliest sculpture, the earliest painting, the earliest writing, it is sacred -- sculpture and painting and writing. So that all these arts were of course originally wrapped up in the same sense of magic as was religion. What has happened with the passage of the years is that they have gone down separate roads. But both have the same interest in magic it's just that one is not necessarily interested in the kind of magic called religion. And there's a, Aurora for instance, who is entirely godless in <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I> as indeed are a large proportion of the characters, rather untypically for India, but Aurora says at one point of her work that she has become more and more interested in painting religious pictures for people who have no god.  That formulation also represents something of my view. I think it's very, the concentration and force that religious stories have, the kind of compression of meaning in those stories is very, very intense. Therefore they pack an incredible punch. I've always thought that it would be desirable to find ways of trying to equal or rival that emotional, intellectual and indeed moral concentration but also narrative concentration of force without necessarily leading towards a religious moral.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I wanted to speak to you about that concentration or compaction. On the one hand you have, Blake infinity in a grain of sand, but there's a funny quality, and it is <I>Finnegan's Wake</I>-like, that within moments, layer upon layer of these books reveal plots folded upon or performing versions of one another. For instance, at the end of this book, in which of course art reveals reality, art reveals a murder and it's a murder whose perpetrator is a shocking surprise. In that act of revelation, simultaneously, one finds Wilde's <I>Dorian Gray</I> referred to and in this book it's a particular because whereas the hero of <I>Dorian Gray</I> does not age, the hero of this book ages twice as rapidly as any painting of him could and his mother paints him constantly. And also the famous story by Edgar Allen Poe, <I>The Oval Portrait</I>. So that there's a kind of constellation of meaning around every...

<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> I think that's so. And I think that not all readers would get all the meanings and in a way it's not absolutely important that they do. I think a lot of this has to do with flavoring. Lot of this has to do with making sure the soup has a density of flavor that people will enjoy when they taste the soup without necessarily being able to identify every ingredient. And I think that's one reason why I take pleasure in putting in all the layers of reference. Particularly in a novel like <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>, which is a novel about layering, whose subject is that reality as we experience it is not what it seems, that there is this bright overworld that we live in which contains the sensuality of life and also the dailyness of life, the things we know about life. But every so often the picture cracks and there comes bubbling up from the cracks, oozing up from the cracks, an underworld which is altogether another thing, blacker and harder to comprehend and more dangerous. The thing I wanted to suggest by creating in the book these layers of overworld and underworld is to suggest that both these worlds are true.  Not to say that the surface world is false and that true reality is only what you find beneath, I think that would be an excessively paranoid view of the world. Also not to suggest that the darkness is not there. I think both the brightness and the darkness are there and that layering is very important in this book. And so the characters I hope, and incidents, have a certain layering of that sort as well.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> What I think is characteristic in the way in which the swarm of storytelling works, as opposed to in Joyce where you can go for pages being mystified, the point here would seem to be that from childhood on, stories, art, painting, had things to say about everything. It's as if the world is like a mole, burrowing in the vastness of possibility that has been re-represented by art.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> I think that encyclopedist instinct is, which Aurora has in the novel as a painter, is one that I've always had as a writer.  I've always thought there are two ways of writing good books. One is to try to put the whole world in and fail obviously, but fail interestingly. As Beckett said, try again, fail better. Or to take one strand out of the hair of the world and look at that single strand in great detail and to find infinity in it. Now I, by and large, have tended to the former strategy.  And I remember one of the most memorable, to me, reviews of <I>Midnight's Children</I> when it came out, Robert Towers wrote a review in which he likened the architecture of the book to the spire of a Hindu temple. He made the interesting point, which is quite true, that in fact, what you find at the top of a Hindu temple is not what in Christian terms what be understood as a spire, because a spire is something that aspires towards God, it yearns upwards into the sky. Whereas the spire-like object on the top of a Hindu temple is a representation of the world mountains, a representation of the earth. And that's why it teems with figures crawling all over it. It's a representation of as much of humanity as you can possibly put on the mountain. He said that he found my writing to be of that sort. It's rather wonderful when a critic gives you an image of your own work which seems to you to have some truth in it and so you immediately steal it, which is of course what I did.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> The novel begins with a rush of enunciation, in that the hero, having in a sense, dying and completing his manuscript -- one of the things I think that we don't know that Scheherazade got to do -- he simultaneously looks for a place to nail it making him a Martin Luther character. But instead of reaffirmation, it seemed that what he's searching for is reformation. That there's a yearning for things to come back together, not so much for things to be revised as for them to be united.<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Yes, I think that's well said actually because he is somebody for whom the pieces of the world have broken apart in his life. The world he knows has shattered under various pressures including love and hatred and so on, religion, crime, all sorts of very large sledgehammers have been taken to his world. He finds himself at the beginning of the novel at the end of the story. And really his only recourse is language, all he has left is to tell the story of himself, as he says the story that leads to me. He refers to it as the treasure map of himself, the end of it, x marking the spot, is him. He uses that deliberately, the echo of the Martin Luther formation and he says, here I stand I couldn't have done it differently. But yes there's exactly that sense of trying to weld his world back together just through the act of language, the act of telling.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> In the opening pages there's a rush of classic enunciation. He immediately invokes Dante for instance, and not long after Virgil as well. This initiates a whole sense of strands. It's not going to be just classic narrative but movie stories, cartoon stories, photo novellas, every kind of melodrama and low-high-middle form is going to be invoked here as if to say, somewhere there is a truth but only a multiplicity of forms, high and low, could ever arrive at it.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> This is, I'm afraid, just the garbage in my head. I don't deliberately set out to create this melange of form, this high-low, east and west, north and south, jumble sale of literature. It just happens to be what lodges between my ears. Given that every book is an attempt to understand the world, I use the stuff that lodges in my memory. I have, unfortunately, I find it rather strange, a magpie tendency. I remember fragments of everything from Dante to the lyrics of Bob Dylan. I've come to trust that unconscious selective process of my memory. I've come to feel that if I've remembered these things it's because these things are necessary to me. So I make use of them as I can. I think it's right, that Moor, the narrator of this novel, wants to use as a tool of understanding, anything he can lay his hands on whether it's Bugs Bunny or <I>Finnigan's Wake</I>.
  <P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> Toward the end of the book, the hero has become a participant of the kinds of violence that have alienated and imprisoned him. He is a goon, he beats people up with his big deformed fists. He says about beatings that different kinds of beatings damage different parts of the soul, that being beat at the bottom of the feet makes it impossible for the soul to laugh.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> These are technical matters not known by the general public. But it is true, it's a kind of acupuncture equivalent.  It's the acupuncture of violence. That kind of riff on violence is couched in that mock technical way in order to add a layer of comedy to what is, in fact, very far from being comic.  But I wanted to explore in this book the nature of violence because one of the things that informed the way in which the book developed was that during the course of my thinking of it and during the course of my writing it, there were all kinds of acts of what I would call intimate violence that happened in both India and elsewhere.  Bosnia is another example, where people, not the violence of total war where armies clash and the people that you kill are people whose faces you never see or know, but the violence of the communal riots, the violence of the slaughter of your neighbor's children. How do we kill and maim those people with whom we laughed and joked yesterday. That seems to be a particular modern horror of violence. I wanted to try and see where that came from and in order to do that I had to plunge him, the Moor, into a violent world and actually, to show that that violence is in him too. I think that one of the excuses we make and we hear about, appalling atrocities and terrible acts of violence, we excuse ourselves from those acts because we say, how terrible that so-and-so or that they should have done those bad things and how inhumane. We call them animals, we use all these distancing words. It seems to me that these are cop outs, that in fact, if any human being is capable of something than in fact all human beings are capable of it.  The thing is to try and understand what in our natures permits it and drives us towards it. And the answer, or at least an answer, which is not particularly optimistic one, which is that maybe that's what we're like. It may be that this stuff, civilization, discourse, argument, democracy, gentleness, peacefulness, maybe that's the alien clothing that we put on. At one point in the novel the narrator suggests, civilization is the slight of hand by which we conceal our true natures from ourselves.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> The book is a family chronicle and the chronicle widens to include the world, the family widens to include the world. At each stage there is an unleashing of violence in the first generation, the second generation rather, it's a family feud. In each case the reign of violence in initiated by the act of a woman and by the end we're dealing with the reign of Caliuga, a kind of violence unleashed and represented by a particularly lethal and hideous and lying woman and I wondered why that is.
<P><P>
<B>SR:</B> Accidental. I don't think I thought about it. I think in this novel the women are the dynamic force in the novel of all sorts, not just creation but in destruction. So I think it's simply because the women in this story make everything happen. They make everything in the story happen. They make the love in the story happen and they make the hatred in the story happen. I simply found myself writing about this family of super-powerful women and much less powerful, or much less apparently powerful, men. I think that the consequence you mentioned flows naturally from that. In Hindu cosmology there's an interesting aspect of it, which is that the women deities represent the dynamic force of the gods. The male deities kind of represent abstract varieties and the females represent action.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> When you say Indian cosmogony what exactly are you referring to?
<P><P>
<B>SR:</B> In the Hindu pantheon, for instance, you have the idea of Shakti the word which represents the dynamic force of the gods, is a female concept. So that the female deities act and the male deities simply be. Someone once said to me what this means is the men sit at home and the women do all the work which is another way of looking at it. That sense of the potent and active woman who is both creation because of fertility and destruction in the form of Khali is quite central and that develops into the idea of India as mother of a mother which is both creative and destructive. Out of that, I suppose, came the women of this book. I do think that this is a novel about female power. I remember when I first finished it, I did a sort of sneak preview reading of it at a gathering of writers and critics. There were a lot of very eminent British women writers and critics there and I was a bit scared of how they would react. Fortunately they all liked it very much and the thing they said to me afterwards that they liked about it was not just the power of the women but actually their moral ambiguity, the fact that they were capable of horrible acts as well as wonderful acts. And above all, they said, the thing that women were very rarely allowed to be in fiction, was funny. And they liked the fact that Aurora had all the best lines. Which is true the women in this novel are much funnier than the men. <P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> It's interesting about Aurora, she seems to learn her language from her husband's mother whom she hates.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> What I just thought I would do, in the way that many families have a family language, that families have private words for things and private expressions and ways of saying things, and that's one of the essential natures of being inside a family. I wanted to give this family a bit of family language and in this family these peculiar verb endings and things that people tack on descend through the female line. So it's Epiphania and Belle and Aurora who do it. So Belle, Aurora's mother catches it like an infection from Epiphania whom she hates. Aurora then gets it from her mother.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> And Uma gets it too.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Uma gets it too. It's only the women who get it, this linguistic disease specific to women.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I'm curious, is it possible, this is a final question, that the density of these books, because they are this dense, has allowed you to maintain the ability to write through these seven difficult years. That the books, the kinds of creativity that they require would seem to be cocoon like for the writer. They are all about enclosing and enclosing and enclosing and enclosing so that art might itself create a kind of personal safety zone.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> What I would say that to try and write a book like this requires an act of imagination that simply takes up all your available brain space. That in order to hold in one's head for a period of almost five years, a work that grows in complexity as you write it,  and yet then to try and extrude it through your fingertips in a form that's very simple and accessible to enter, well that's a very large imaginative enterprise and it takes you over. So in the end, I found, the sense of what you're saying is right. I found that I was living more richly in this imaginative world than in the real world. I think that's true of any writer at any time when he's working on a book that's going well.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I think that's true of any reader any time, that one of the extraordinary thinks about books that people very rarely talk about is that as you read, the page of the book fills up your entire visual space. It replaces the world and you go across it, left to right, left to right entering a kind of imposed and necessary trance state. It's not the liability of art that it is a replacement world, it's the inevitability of art that it is, it seems to me.
<P>
<P>
<B>SR:</B> Yes, I think that it is the great joy of the art of the novel that in it you meet the entire inner life of a being whom you don't know. And you allow that whole naked, inner life into your own inner life. So you conjoin, the writer and the reader conjoin, within the mind of the reader at a degree of intimacy that no other work of art can provide. With all other works of art they are all outside you, paintings, movies, operas, whatever they are, as great as they are, they are all outside you.  The book functions, it gets right inside you. The books that you love become a part of you and you never lose them and that's the best reason I've ever thought of for writing them.
<P>
<P>
<B>MS:</B> I've been speaking to Salman Rushdie, the author most recently of <I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I>, published by Pantheon. It's been a pleasure and honor to talk to you.<P><P><B>SR:</B> Thank you very much.<P><FONT SIZE = -1>Copyright 1996 KCRW and Michael Silverblatt.  All rights reserved.</FONT></TT>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQU
</DOC>
